{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780729352095,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbd8f9d001UICq4ewqex2tYA","messageID":"msg_e9bbd8857001Jxpg3QelvxEs1Q","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","snapshot":"35436d92ed68b8c675d18245014a5c56bc93e7d5","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729360378,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_LS3Z51iIGpc0MFjgQ3dFp4pl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","offset":418,"limit":190},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n418: def _with_latency(result: str, t0: float) -> str | CallToolResult:\n419:     \"\"\"Stamp the response with ``_latency_ms`` — and promote error\n420:     envelopes to ``CallToolResult(isError=True)``.\n421: \n422:     Returns:\n423:       - ``str`` for success payloads (JSON dict with latency injected,\n424:         or non-JSON text with a trailing ``_latency_ms:`` line). The\n425:         FastMCP framework wraps these into ``CallToolResult(isError=\n426:         False)`` by default — the prior behavior for success paths.\n427:       - ``CallToolResult(isError=True)`` for ``{\"error\": {...}}``\n428:         envelopes produced by ``_error_response``. The JSON envelope\n429:         (including ``_latency_ms``) is preserved verbatim in a single\n430:         TextContent so any client doing\n431:         ``json.loads(result.content[0].text)`` keeps seeing the same\n432:         shape — only ``result.isError`` flips. CAURA-000\n433:         (FRICTION-REPORT-V3 B2).\n434:     \"\"\"\n435:     ms = round((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000)\n436:     try:\n437:         data = json.loads(result)\n438:         if isinstance(data, dict):\n439:             data[\"_latency_ms\"] = ms\n440:             payload = json.dumps(data, default=str)\n441:             if isinstance(data.get(\"error\"), dict):\n442:                 return _as_error_result(payload)\n443:             return payload\n444:     except (json.JSONDecodeError, ValueError):\n445:         pass\n446:     return result + f\"\\n\\n_latency_ms: {ms}\"\n447: \n448: \n449: # ── Tools ──\n450: \n451: \n452: async def memclaw_recall(\n453:     query: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"NL query.\")],\n454:     agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n455:     filter_agent_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Filter by author.\")] = None,\n456:     memory_type: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Filter by type.\")] = None,\n457:     status: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Filter by status.\")] = None,\n458:     fleet_ids: Annotated[list[str] | None, Field(description=\"Restrict fleets.\")] = None,\n459:     include_brief: Annotated[bool, Field(description=\"Add LLM summary.\")] = False,\n460:     top_k: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"1-20.\")] = DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n461: ) -> str:\n462:     \"\"\"Hybrid semantic+keyword recall, with optional LLM brief.\"\"\"\n463:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n464:     if err := _check_auth():\n465:         return err\n466:     if memory_type and memory_type not in MEMORY_TYPES:\n467:         return _with_latency(\n468:             _error_response(\n469:                 \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n470:                 f\"Invalid memory_type '{memory_type}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(MEMORY_TYPES)}\",\n471:                 field=\"memory_type\",\n472:                 value=memory_type,\n473:             ),\n474:             t0,\n475:         )\n476:     if status and status not in MEMORY_STATUSES:\n477:         return _with_latency(\n478:             _error_response(\n479:                 \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n480:                 f\"Invalid status '{status}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(MEMORY_STATUSES)}\",\n481:                 field=\"status\",\n482:                 value=status,\n483:             ),\n484:             t0,\n485:         )\n486:     tenant_id = _get_tenant()\n487:     agent_id = _get_agent_id() or agent_id  # prefer gateway-verified identity\n488:     if refuse := _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id):\n489:         return _with_latency(refuse, t0)\n490:     capped_top_k = min(top_k, MAX_SEARCH_TOP_K)\n491: \n492:     # Audit finding P3: prior implementation held ``_mcp_session()``\n493:     # open across the brief-generation LLM round-trip (~5-30s), pinning\n494:     # a pooled DB connection during work that is entirely network-bound\n495:     # to the LLM provider. The brief path also issued a duplicate\n496:     # ``search_memories`` call (once here, once inside ``recall()``).\n497:     # Both are fixed by doing all DB-bound work inside the session,\n498:     # capturing the search results + config + readable-tenant set, then\n499:     # closing the session before invoking ``summarize_memories`` for\n500:     # the LLM brief.\n501:     try:\n502:         async with _mcp_session() as db:\n503:             await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"search\")\n504:             from core_api.repositories import agent_repo\n505:             from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n506: \n507:             config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n508:             _ag = await agent_repo.get_by_id(db, agent_id, tenant_id)\n509:             agent_profile = None\n510:             if _ag:\n511:                 agent_profile = _ag.get(\"search_profile\") if isinstance(_ag, dict) else _ag.search_profile\n512:             # Fleet scope enforcement (parity with REST /search): a constrained\n513:             # agent that omits fleet_ids is scoped to its own fleet, and a single\n514:             # explicit fleet goes through the cross-fleet trust ladder. Closes the\n515:             # recall side of the cross-fleet content leak.\n516:             if _ag is not None and not fleet_ids:\n517:                 ag_fleet = _ag.get(\"fleet_id\") if isinstance(_ag, dict) else getattr(_ag, \"fleet_id\", None)\n518:                 ag_trust = (\n519:                     _ag.get(\"trust_level\", 0) if isinstance(_ag, dict) else getattr(_ag, \"trust_level\", 0)\n520:                 )\n521:                 if ag_fleet and ag_trust < 2:\n522:                     fleet_ids = [ag_fleet]\n523:             if fleet_ids and len(fleet_ids) == 1:\n524:                 await enforce_fleet_read(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_ids[0])\n525:             # Cross-tenant recall widens via readable_tenant_ids when\n526:             # the caller authenticated with a cross-tenant credential\n527:             # (kind=cross_tenant) — the gateway plumbs\n528:             # ``X-Readable-Tenant-IDs`` and the MCP middleware parks\n529:             # it on ``_readable_tenant_ids_var``. Single-tenant\n530:             # credentials leave the var empty; ``search_memories`` falls\n531:             # back to ``WHERE tenant_id = $1`` in that case.\n532:             results = await search_memories(\n533:                 db,\n534:                 tenant_id=tenant_id,\n535:                 query=query,\n536:                 fleet_ids=fleet_ids,\n537:                 filter_agent_id=filter_agent_id,\n538:                 caller_agent_id=agent_id,\n539:                 memory_type_filter=memory_type,\n540:                 status_filter=status,\n541:                 top_k=capped_top_k,\n542:                 recall_boost=config.recall_boost,\n543:                 graph_expand=config.graph_expand,\n544:                 tenant_config=config,\n545:                 search_profile=agent_profile,\n546:                 readable_tenant_ids=_get_readable_tenants() or None,\n547:             )\n548:             # Cross-tenant read audit (F2): emit one event per source\n549:             # tenant when the credential widened beyond home. Async\n550:             # queue — does not block the response.\n551:             readable = _get_readable_tenants()\n552:             source_tenants = [t for t in readable if t and t != tenant_id]\n553:             if source_tenants:\n554:                 await log_cross_tenant_read(\n555:                     db,\n556:                     home_tenant_id=tenant_id,\n557:                     home_agent_id=agent_id,\n558:                     source_tenants=source_tenants,\n559:                     surface=\"memclaw_recall\",\n560:                     query_summary=(query or \"\")[:200],\n561:                 )\n562:         # ── Session closed; the LLM brief (when requested) runs without\n563:         # holding a DB connection.\n564:         payload: dict = {\n565:             \"results\": [r.model_dump(mode=\"json\") for r in results] if results else [],\n566:         }\n567:         if include_brief:\n568:             from core_api.services.recall_service import summarize_memories\n569: \n570:             payload[\"brief\"] = await summarize_memories(\n571:                 results,\n572:                 query,\n573:                 config,\n574:                 top_k=capped_top_k,\n575:             )\n576:         return _with_latency(json.dumps(payload, indent=2, default=str), t0)\n577:     except HTTPException as e:\n578:         logger.warning(\"MCP tool error (%s): %s\", e.status_code, e.detail)\n579:         return _with_latency(_error_response(code_for_status(e.status_code), str(e.detail)), t0)\n580: \n581: \n582: async def memclaw_write(\n583:     content: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Single-write text.\")] = None,\n584:     items: Annotated[\n585:         list[dict] | None, Field(description=\"Batch of objects, ≤100; each needs 'content'.\")\n586:     ] = None,\n587:     agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n588:     fleet_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Fleet scope.\")] = None,\n589:     visibility: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"scope_team|scope_org|scope_agent.\")] = None,\n590:     memory_type: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Type (single only).\")] = None,\n591:     weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"0-1 (single only).\")] = None,\n592:     source_uri: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Source URI (single only).\")] = None,\n593:     run_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Run id (single only).\")] = None,\n594:     metadata: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"Metadata (single only).\")] = None,\n595:     status: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Status (single only).\")] = None,\n596:     write_mode: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"fast|strong|auto (single only).\")] = None,\n597: ) -> str:\n598:     \"\"\"Single OR batch write. Exactly one of {content, items} is required.\"\"\"\n599:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n600:     if err := _check_auth():\n601:         return err\n602:     if err := _check_write_scope():\n603:         return err\n604:     if (content is None) == (items is None):\n605:         return _with_latency(\n606:             json.dumps(\n607:                 {\n\n(Showing lines 418-607 of 2542. Use offset=608 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"def _with_latency(result: str, t0: float) -> str | CallToolResult:\n    \"\"\"Stamp the response with ``_latency_ms`` — and promote error\n    envelopes to ``CallToolResult(isError=True)``.\n\n    Returns:\n      - ``str`` for success payloads (JSON dict with latency injected,\n        or non-JSON text with a trailing ``_latency_ms:`` line). The\n        FastMCP framework wraps these into ``CallToolResult(isError=\n        False)`` by default — the prior behavior for success paths.\n      - ``CallToolResult(isError=True)`` for ``{\"error\": {...}}``\n        envelopes produced by ``_error_response``. The JSON envelope\n        (including ``_latency_ms``) is preserved verbatim in a single\n        TextContent so any client doing\n        ``json.loads(result.content[0].text)`` keeps seeing the same\n        shape — only ``result.isError`` flips. CAURA-000\n        (FRICTION-REPORT-V3 B2).\n    \"\"\"\n    ms = round((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000)\n    try:\n        data = json.loads(result)","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","text":"def _with_latency(result: str, t0: float) -> str | CallToolResult:\n    \"\"\"Stamp the response with ``_latency_ms`` — and promote error\n    envelopes to ``CallToolResult(isError=True)``.\n\n    Returns:\n      - ``str`` for success payloads (JSON dict with latency injected,\n        or non-JSON text with a trailing ``_latency_ms:`` line). The\n        FastMCP framework wraps these into ``CallToolResult(isError=\n        False)`` by default — the prior behavior for success paths.\n      - ``CallToolResult(isError=True)`` for ``{\"error\": {...}}``\n        envelopes produced by ``_error_response``. The JSON envelope\n        (including ``_latency_ms``) is preserved verbatim in a single\n        TextContent so any client doing\n        ``json.loads(result.content[0].text)`` keeps seeing the same\n        shape — only ``result.isError`` flips. CAURA-000\n        (FRICTION-REPORT-V3 B2).\n    \"\"\"\n    ms = round((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000)\n    try:\n        data = json.loads(result)\n        if isinstance(data, dict):\n            data[\"_latency_ms\"] = ms\n            payload = json.dumps(data, default=str)\n            if isinstance(data.get(\"error\"), dict):\n                return _as_error_result(payload)\n            return payload\n    except (json.JSONDecodeError, ValueError):\n        pass\n    return result + f\"\\n\\n_latency_ms: {ms}\"\n\n\n# ── Tools ──\n\n\nasync def memclaw_recall(\n    query: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"NL query.\")],\n    agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n    filter_agent_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Filter by author.\")] = None,\n    memory_type: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Filter by type.\")] = None,\n    status: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Filter by status.\")] = None,\n    fleet_ids: Annotated[list[str] | None, Field(description=\"Restrict fleets.\")] = None,\n    include_brief: Annotated[bool, Field(description=\"Add LLM summary.\")] = False,\n    top_k: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"1-20.\")] = DEFAULT_SEARCH_TOP_K,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Hybrid semantic+keyword recall, with optional LLM brief.\"\"\"\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n    if err := _check_auth():\n        return err\n    if memory_type and memory_type not in MEMORY_TYPES:\n        return _with_latency(\n            _error_response(\n                \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n                f\"Invalid memory_type '{memory_type}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(MEMORY_TYPES)}\",\n                field=\"memory_type\",\n                value=memory_type,\n            ),\n            t0,\n        )\n    if status and status not in MEMORY_STATUSES:\n        return _with_latency(\n            _error_response(\n                \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n                f\"Invalid status '{status}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(MEMORY_STATUSES)}\",\n                field=\"status\",\n                value=status,\n            ),\n            t0,\n        )\n    tenant_id = _get_tenant()\n    agent_id = _get_agent_id() or agent_id  # prefer gateway-verified identity\n    if refuse := _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id):\n        return _with_latency(refuse, t0)\n    capped_top_k = min(top_k, MAX_SEARCH_TOP_K)\n\n    # Audit finding P3: prior implementation held ``_mcp_session()``\n    # open across the brief-generation LLM round-trip (~5-30s), pinning\n    # a pooled DB connection during work that is entirely network-bound\n    # to the LLM provider. The brief path also issued a duplicate\n    # ``search_memories`` call (once here, once inside ``recall()``).\n    # Both are fixed by doing all DB-bound work inside the session,\n    # capturing the search results + config + readable-tenant set, then\n    # closing the session before invoking ``summarize_memories`` for\n    # the LLM brief.\n    try:\n        async with _mcp_session() as db:\n            await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"search\")\n            from core_api.repositories import agent_repo\n            from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n\n            config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n            _ag = await agent_repo.get_by_id(db, agent_id, tenant_id)\n            agent_profile = None\n            if _ag:\n                agent_profile = _ag.get(\"search_profile\") if isinstance(_ag, dict) else _ag.search_profile\n            # Fleet scope enforcement (parity with REST /search): a constrained\n            # agent that omits fleet_ids is scoped to its own fleet, and a single\n            # explicit fleet goes through the cross-fleet trust ladder. Closes the\n            # recall side of the cross-fleet content leak.\n            if _ag is not None and not fleet_ids:\n                ag_fleet = _ag.get(\"fleet_id\") if isinstance(_ag, dict) else getattr(_ag, \"fleet_id\", None)\n                ag_trust = (\n                    _ag.get(\"trust_level\", 0) if isinstance(_ag, dict) else getattr(_ag, \"trust_level\", 0)\n                )\n                if ag_fleet and ag_trust < 2:\n                    fleet_ids = [ag_fleet]\n            if fleet_ids and len(fleet_ids) == 1:\n                await enforce_fleet_read(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_ids[0])\n            # Cross-tenant recall widens via readable_tenant_ids when\n            # the caller authenticated with a cross-tenant credential\n            # (kind=cross_tenant) — the gateway plumbs\n            # ``X-Readable-Tenant-IDs`` and the MCP middleware parks\n            # it on ``_readable_tenant_ids_var``. Single-tenant\n            # credentials leave the var empty; ``search_memories`` falls\n            # back to ``WHERE tenant_id = $1`` in that case.\n            results = await search_memories(\n                db,\n                tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                query=query,\n                fleet_ids=fleet_ids,\n                filter_agent_id=filter_agent_id,\n                caller_agent_id=agent_id,\n                memory_type_filter=memory_type,\n                status_filter=status,\n                top_k=capped_top_k,\n                recall_boost=config.recall_boost,\n                graph_expand=config.graph_expand,\n                tenant_config=config,\n                search_profile=agent_profile,\n                readable_tenant_ids=_get_readable_tenants() or None,\n            )\n            # Cross-tenant read audit (F2): emit one event per source\n            # tenant when the credential widened beyond home. Async\n            # queue — does not block the response.\n            readable = _get_readable_tenants()\n            source_tenants = [t for t in readable if t and t != tenant_id]\n            if source_tenants:\n                await log_cross_tenant_read(\n                    db,\n                    home_tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    home_agent_id=agent_id,\n                    source_tenants=source_tenants,\n                    surface=\"memclaw_recall\",\n                    query_summary=(query or \"\")[:200],\n                )\n        # ── Session closed; the LLM brief (when requested) runs without\n        # holding a DB connection.\n        payload: dict = {\n            \"results\": [r.model_dump(mode=\"json\") for r in results] if results else [],\n        }\n        if include_brief:\n            from core_api.services.recall_service import summarize_memories\n\n            payload[\"brief\"] = await summarize_memories(\n                results,\n                query,\n                config,\n                top_k=capped_top_k,\n            )\n        return _with_latency(json.dumps(payload, indent=2, default=str), t0)\n    except HTTPException as e:\n        logger.warning(\"MCP tool error (%s): %s\", e.status_code, e.detail)\n        return _with_latency(_error_response(code_for_status(e.status_code), str(e.detail)), t0)\n\n\nasync def memclaw_write(\n    content: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Single-write text.\")] = None,\n    items: Annotated[\n        list[dict] | None, Field(description=\"Batch of objects, ≤100; each needs 'content'.\")\n    ] = None,\n    agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n    fleet_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Fleet scope.\")] = None,\n    visibility: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"scope_team|scope_org|scope_agent.\")] = None,\n    memory_type: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Type (single only).\")] = None,\n    weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"0-1 (single only).\")] = None,\n    source_uri: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Source URI (single only).\")] = None,\n    run_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Run id (single only).\")] = None,\n    metadata: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"Metadata (single only).\")] = None,\n    status: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"Status (single only).\")] = None,\n    write_mode: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"fast|strong|auto (single only).\")] = None,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Single OR batch write. Exactly one of {content, items} is required.\"\"\"\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n    if err := _check_auth():\n        return err\n    if err := _check_write_scope():\n        return err\n    if (content is None) == (items is None):\n        return _with_latency(\n            json.dumps(\n                {","lineStart":418,"lineEnd":607,"totalLines":2542,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","time":{"start":1780729360371,"end":1780729360376}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055aada8abc9d1d5016a23c61055148191a956afbd94bf01b5"}},"id":"prt_e9bbdaff2001gL7jmgY1EGEZwy","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbd8857001Jxpg3QelvxEs1Q"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729360417,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_VhYKzvdYeOlvSn2VForBty3w","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","offset":735,"limit":345},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n735: async def memclaw_manage(\n736:     op: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"read|update|transition|delete|bulk_delete|lineage.\")],\n737:     memory_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"UUID. Required except for op=bulk_delete.\")] = \"\",\n738:     memory_ids: Annotated[\n739:         list[str] | None,\n740:         Field(description=\"op=bulk_delete: list of memory UUIDs (max 1000).\"),\n741:     ] = None,\n742:     status: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=transition.\")] = None,\n743:     content: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n744:     memory_type: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n745:     weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"op=update; 0-1.\")] = None,\n746:     title: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n747:     metadata: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n748:     source_uri: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n749:     agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n750: ) -> str:\n751:     \"\"\"Per-memory lifecycle: read | update | transition | delete | bulk_delete | lineage.\n752: \n753:     op=lineage walks the supersession chain for `memory_id` and returns\n754:     {this, superseded_by, supersessors} — the older row this memory\n755:     replaced (if any) and any newer rows that supersede this one.\n756:     Mirrors the focused agent-facing view of REST `/memories/{id}/contradictions`.\n757:     \"\"\"\n758:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n759:     if err := _check_auth():\n760:         return err\n761:     _valid_ops = {\"read\", \"update\", \"transition\", \"delete\", \"bulk_delete\", \"lineage\"}\n762:     if op not in _valid_ops:\n763:         return _with_latency(\n764:             json.dumps(\n765:                 {\n766:                     \"error\": {\n767:                         \"code\": \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n768:                         \"message\": f\"Unknown op '{op}'. Expected one of: {sorted(_valid_ops)}.\",\n769:                         \"details\": {\"op\": op, \"expected_ops\": sorted(_valid_ops)},\n770:                     }\n771:                 }\n772:             ),\n773:             t0,\n774:         )\n775:     # Mutating ops gated by the credential scope set; read/lineage stay open\n776:     # to read-only keys.\n777:     if op in {\"update\", \"transition\", \"delete\", \"bulk_delete\"} and (err := _check_write_scope()):\n778:         return err\n779:     # bulk_delete uses memory_ids (list); all other ops use memory_id (single UUID).\n780:     # Validate accordingly so a missing memory_id on bulk_delete doesn't fail with\n781:     # a misleading \"Invalid UUID\" error.\n782:     if op != \"bulk_delete\":\n783:         try:\n784:             uid = UUID(memory_id)\n785:         except ValueError:\n786:             return _with_latency(\n787:                 _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"Invalid memory_id — must be a valid UUID.\"),\n788:                 t0,\n789:             )\n790:     tenant_id = _get_tenant()\n791:     # Raw authenticated identity (gateway-resolved). Used for fleet/scope\n792:     # authorization — must NOT fall back to the ``mcp-agent`` default, or an\n793:     # unauthenticated caller would inherit that identity's scope. ``None`` ⇒\n794:     # no agent context (OSS/standalone) ⇒ tenant-scoped, no agent isolation.\n795:     caller_agent_id = _get_agent_id()\n796:     agent_id = caller_agent_id or agent_id\n797:     if op in {\"update\", \"transition\", \"delete\", \"bulk_delete\"} and (\n798:         refuse := _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id)\n799:     ):\n800:         return _with_latency(refuse, t0)\n801: \n802:     async with _mcp_session() as db:\n803:         try:\n804:             if op == \"bulk_delete\":\n805:                 if not memory_ids:\n806:                     return _with_latency(\n807:                         _error_response(\n808:                             \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=bulk_delete requires non-empty 'memory_ids'.\"\n809:                         ),\n810:                         t0,\n811:                     )\n812:                 if len(memory_ids) > 1000:\n813:                     return _with_latency(\n814:                         _error_response(\n815:                             \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", f\"op=bulk_delete capped at 1000 ids (got {len(memory_ids)}).\"\n816:                         ),\n817:                         t0,\n818:                     )\n819:                 try:\n820:                     uids = [UUID(i) for i in memory_ids]\n821:                 except ValueError as e:\n822:                     return _with_latency(\n823:                         _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", f\"invalid UUID in memory_ids — {e}\"), t0\n824:                     )\n825:                 # Trust gate (>= 3), mirroring single delete / REST DELETE. Blocks\n826:                 # the cross-fleet bulk-delete-by-id IDOR for sub-admin agents; a\n827:                 # trust>=3 admin agent retains tenant-wide delete (parity with\n828:                 # enforce_fleet_write). No-op for tenant-scoped credentials.\n829:                 if caller_agent_id:\n830:                     await enforce_delete(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id)\n831:                 from datetime import UTC\n832:                 from datetime import datetime as _dt\n833: \n834:                 from sqlalchemy import update as _sa_update\n835: \n836:                 from common.models.memory import Memory as _Mem\n837: \n838:                 stmt = (\n839:                     _sa_update(_Mem)\n840:                     .where(\n841:                         _Mem.tenant_id == tenant_id,\n842:                         _Mem.id.in_(uids),\n843:                         _Mem.deleted_at.is_(None),\n844:                     )\n845:                     .values(deleted_at=_dt.now(UTC), status=\"deleted\")\n846:                 )\n847:                 result = await db.execute(stmt)\n848:                 await log_action(\n849:                     db,\n850:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n851:                     agent_id=agent_id,\n852:                     action=\"bulk_delete\",\n853:                     resource_type=\"memory\",\n854:                     detail={\"count\": result.rowcount, \"method\": \"by_ids\", \"via\": \"mcp\"},\n855:                 )\n856:                 await db.commit()\n857:                 return _with_latency(json.dumps({\"deleted\": result.rowcount, \"requested\": len(uids)}), t0)\n858:             if op == \"lineage\":\n859:                 from sqlalchemy import select as _sa_select\n860: \n861:                 from common.models.memory import Memory as _Mem\n862: \n863:                 this = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n864:                 if not this:\n865:                     return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n866:                 # Fleet/agent-scope authorization (mirrors op=read): the\n867:                 # supersession chain would otherwise leak a scoped row by id.\n868:                 if not await authorize_memory_access(\n869:                     db,\n870:                     tenant_id,\n871:                     caller_agent_id,\n872:                     visibility=this.visibility,\n873:                     owner_agent_id=this.agent_id,\n874:                     fleet_id=this.fleet_id,\n875:                 ):\n876:                     return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n877: \n878:                 # The older memory this row replaced (if any). The\n879:                 # supersedes_id field points at the OLDER row (the\n880:                 # detector's \"loser\"); this row was the winner.\n881:                 superseded_by = None\n882:                 if this.supersedes_id:\n883:                     older = await db.get(_Mem, this.supersedes_id)\n884:                     if older and older.tenant_id == tenant_id and older.deleted_at is None:\n885:                         superseded_by = {\n886:                             \"id\": str(older.id),\n887:                             \"content_preview\": older.content[:200],\n888:                             \"status\": older.status,\n889:                             \"created_at\": (older.created_at.isoformat() if older.created_at else None),\n890:                         }\n891: \n892:                 # Newer rows whose supersedes_id points at this row\n893:                 # (this row was their \"loser\").\n894:                 stmt = (\n895:                     _sa_select(_Mem)\n896:                     .where(\n897:                         _Mem.supersedes_id == uid,\n898:                         _Mem.tenant_id == tenant_id,\n899:                         _Mem.deleted_at.is_(None),\n900:                     )\n901:                     .order_by(_Mem.created_at.desc())\n902:                 )\n903:                 supersessors = [\n904:                     {\n905:                         \"id\": str(m.id),\n906:                         \"content_preview\": m.content[:200],\n907:                         \"status\": m.status,\n908:                         \"created_at\": m.created_at.isoformat() if m.created_at else None,\n909:                     }\n910:                     for m in (await db.execute(stmt)).scalars().all()\n911:                 ]\n912:                 return _with_latency(\n913:                     json.dumps(\n914:                         {\n915:                             \"this\": {\n916:                                 \"id\": str(this.id),\n917:                                 \"status\": this.status,\n918:                                 \"supersedes_id\": (str(this.supersedes_id) if this.supersedes_id else None),\n919:                             },\n920:                             \"superseded_by\": superseded_by,  # the OLDER row this replaced\n921:                             \"supersessors\": supersessors,  # NEWER rows that replaced this\n922:                         },\n923:                         default=str,\n924:                     ),\n925:                     t0,\n926:                 )\n927:             if op == \"read\":\n928:                 memory = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n929:                 if not memory:\n930:                     return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n931:                 # Fleet/agent-scope authorization: honor the same scope_agent +\n932:                 # cross-fleet trust ladder the search/list paths enforce, so an\n933:                 # agent can't read a peer's scoped row by id. NOT_FOUND (not\n934:                 # PERMISSION_DENIED) to avoid confirming the id exists.\n935:                 if not await authorize_memory_access(\n936:                     db,\n937:                     tenant_id,\n938:                     caller_agent_id,\n939:                     visibility=memory.visibility,\n940:                     owner_agent_id=memory.agent_id,\n941:                     fleet_id=memory.fleet_id,\n942:                 ):\n943:                     return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n944:                 return _with_latency(\n945:                     json.dumps(\n946:                         {\n947:                             \"id\": str(memory.id),\n948:                             \"content\": memory.content,\n949:                             \"memory_type\": memory.memory_type,\n950:                             \"status\": memory.status,\n951:                             \"weight\": memory.weight,\n952:                             \"agent_id\": memory.agent_id,\n953:                             \"fleet_id\": memory.fleet_id,\n954:                             \"visibility\": memory.visibility,\n955:                             \"title\": getattr(memory, \"title\", None),\n956:                             \"created_at\": memory.created_at.isoformat() if memory.created_at else None,\n957:                             \"last_recalled_at\": (\n958:                                 memory.last_recalled_at.isoformat()\n959:                                 if getattr(memory, \"last_recalled_at\", None)\n960:                                 else None\n961:                             ),\n962:                             \"recall_count\": getattr(memory, \"recall_count\", 0),\n963:                             \"deleted_at\": (\n964:                                 memory.deleted_at.isoformat() if getattr(memory, \"deleted_at\", None) else None\n965:                             ),\n966:                             \"metadata\": getattr(memory, \"metadata_\", None),\n967:                         },\n968:                         default=str,\n969:                     ),\n970:                     t0,\n971:                 )\n972:             if op == \"transition\":\n973:                 if not status:\n974:                     return _with_latency(\n975:                         _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=transition requires 'status'.\"), t0\n976:                     )\n977:                 if status not in MEMORY_STATUSES:\n978:                     return _with_latency(\n979:                         _error_response(\n980:                             \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n981:                             f\"Invalid status '{status}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(MEMORY_STATUSES)}\",\n982:                         ),\n983:                         t0,\n984:                     )\n985:                 memory = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n986:                 if not memory:\n987:                     return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n988:                 # Cross-fleet / scope_agent authorization (write threshold).\n989:                 if not await authorize_memory_access(\n990:                     db,\n991:                     tenant_id,\n992:                     caller_agent_id,\n993:                     visibility=memory.visibility,\n994:                     owner_agent_id=memory.agent_id,\n995:                     fleet_id=memory.fleet_id,\n996:                     write=True,\n997:                 ):\n998:                     return _with_latency(\n999:                         _error_response(\n1000:                             \"PERMISSION_DENIED\",\n1001:                             f\"Agent cannot modify memory in fleet '{memory.fleet_id}'.\",\n1002:                         ),\n1003:                         t0,\n1004:                     )\n1005:                 old_status = memory.status\n1006:                 await memory_repo.update_status(db, uid, status)\n1007:                 await log_action(\n1008:                     db,\n1009:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n1010:                     agent_id=memory.agent_id,\n1011:                     action=\"status_update\",\n1012:                     resource_type=\"memory\",\n1013:                     resource_id=uid,\n1014:                     detail={\"old_status\": old_status, \"new_status\": status},\n1015:                 )\n1016:                 await db.commit()\n1017:                 return _with_latency(f\"Memory {memory_id} status updated: {old_status} -> {status}\", t0)\n1018:             if op == \"update\":\n1019:                 fields: dict = {}\n1020:                 if content is not None:\n1021:                     fields[\"content\"] = content\n1022:                 if memory_type is not None:\n1023:                     fields[\"memory_type\"] = memory_type\n1024:                 if weight is not None:\n1025:                     fields[\"weight\"] = weight\n1026:                 if title is not None:\n1027:                     fields[\"title\"] = title\n1028:                 if status is not None:\n1029:                     fields[\"status\"] = status\n1030:                 if metadata is not None:\n1031:                     fields[\"metadata\"] = metadata\n1032:                 if source_uri is not None:\n1033:                     fields[\"source_uri\"] = source_uri\n1034:                 if not fields:\n1035:                     return _with_latency(\n1036:                         _error_response(\n1037:                             \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n1038:                             \"No fields to update. Provide at least one field to change.\",\n1039:                         ),\n1040:                         t0,\n1041:                     )\n1042:                 await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n1043:                 result = await update_memory(db, uid, tenant_id, MemoryUpdate(**fields), agent_id=agent_id)\n1044:                 return _with_latency(_serialize(result), t0)\n1045:             # op == \"delete\"\n1046:             if caller_agent_id:\n1047:                 # Trust gate (>= 3) + cross-fleet / scope_agent row authorization,\n1048:                 # mirroring REST DELETE /memories/{id}.\n1049:                 await enforce_delete(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id)\n1050:                 target = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n1051:                 if target and not await authorize_memory_access(\n1052:                     db,\n1053:                     tenant_id,\n1054:                     caller_agent_id,\n1055:                     visibility=target.visibility,\n1056:                     owner_agent_id=target.agent_id,\n1057:                     fleet_id=target.fleet_id,\n1058:                     write=True,\n1059:                 ):\n1060:                     return _with_latency(\n1061:                         _error_response(\n1062:                             \"PERMISSION_DENIED\",\n1063:                             f\"Agent cannot delete memory in fleet '{target.fleet_id}'.\",\n1064:                         ),\n1065:                         t0,\n1066:                     )\n1067:             await soft_delete_memory(db, uid, tenant_id)\n1068:             return _with_latency(f\"Memory {memory_id} deleted.\", t0)\n1069:         except HTTPException as e:\n1070:             logger.warning(\"MCP tool error (%s): %s\", e.status_code, e.detail)\n1071:             return _with_latency(_error_response(code_for_status(e.status_code), str(e.detail)), t0)\n1072: \n1073: \n1074: async def memclaw_entity_get(\n1075:     entity_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"The UUID of the entity to look up.\")],\n1076: ) -> str:\n1077:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n1078:     if err := _check_auth():\n1079:         return err\n\n(Showing lines 735-1079 of 2542. Use offset=1080 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"async def memclaw_manage(\n    op: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"read|update|transition|delete|bulk_delete|lineage.\")],\n    memory_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"UUID. Required except for op=bulk_delete.\")] = \"\",\n    memory_ids: Annotated[\n        list[str] | None,\n        Field(description=\"op=bulk_delete: list of memory UUIDs (max 1000).\"),\n    ] = None,\n    status: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=transition.\")] = None,\n    content: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    memory_type: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"op=update; 0-1.\")] = None,\n    title: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    metadata: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    source_uri: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Per-memory lifecycle: read | update | transition | delete | bulk_delete | lineage.\n\n    op=lineage walks the supersession chain for `memory_id` and returns\n    {this, superseded_by, supersessors} — the older row this memory","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","text":"async def memclaw_manage(\n    op: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"read|update|transition|delete|bulk_delete|lineage.\")],\n    memory_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"UUID. Required except for op=bulk_delete.\")] = \"\",\n    memory_ids: Annotated[\n        list[str] | None,\n        Field(description=\"op=bulk_delete: list of memory UUIDs (max 1000).\"),\n    ] = None,\n    status: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=transition.\")] = None,\n    content: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    memory_type: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"op=update; 0-1.\")] = None,\n    title: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    metadata: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    source_uri: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=update.\")] = None,\n    agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Per-memory lifecycle: read | update | transition | delete | bulk_delete | lineage.\n\n    op=lineage walks the supersession chain for `memory_id` and returns\n    {this, superseded_by, supersessors} — the older row this memory\n    replaced (if any) and any newer rows that supersede this one.\n    Mirrors the focused agent-facing view of REST `/memories/{id}/contradictions`.\n    \"\"\"\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n    if err := _check_auth():\n        return err\n    _valid_ops = {\"read\", \"update\", \"transition\", \"delete\", \"bulk_delete\", \"lineage\"}\n    if op not in _valid_ops:\n        return _with_latency(\n            json.dumps(\n                {\n                    \"error\": {\n                        \"code\": \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n                        \"message\": f\"Unknown op '{op}'. Expected one of: {sorted(_valid_ops)}.\",\n                        \"details\": {\"op\": op, \"expected_ops\": sorted(_valid_ops)},\n                    }\n                }\n            ),\n            t0,\n        )\n    # Mutating ops gated by the credential scope set; read/lineage stay open\n    # to read-only keys.\n    if op in {\"update\", \"transition\", \"delete\", \"bulk_delete\"} and (err := _check_write_scope()):\n        return err\n    # bulk_delete uses memory_ids (list); all other ops use memory_id (single UUID).\n    # Validate accordingly so a missing memory_id on bulk_delete doesn't fail with\n    # a misleading \"Invalid UUID\" error.\n    if op != \"bulk_delete\":\n        try:\n            uid = UUID(memory_id)\n        except ValueError:\n            return _with_latency(\n                _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"Invalid memory_id — must be a valid UUID.\"),\n                t0,\n            )\n    tenant_id = _get_tenant()\n    # Raw authenticated identity (gateway-resolved). Used for fleet/scope\n    # authorization — must NOT fall back to the ``mcp-agent`` default, or an\n    # unauthenticated caller would inherit that identity's scope. ``None`` ⇒\n    # no agent context (OSS/standalone) ⇒ tenant-scoped, no agent isolation.\n    caller_agent_id = _get_agent_id()\n    agent_id = caller_agent_id or agent_id\n    if op in {\"update\", \"transition\", \"delete\", \"bulk_delete\"} and (\n        refuse := _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id)\n    ):\n        return _with_latency(refuse, t0)\n\n    async with _mcp_session() as db:\n        try:\n            if op == \"bulk_delete\":\n                if not memory_ids:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=bulk_delete requires non-empty 'memory_ids'.\"\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                if len(memory_ids) > 1000:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", f\"op=bulk_delete capped at 1000 ids (got {len(memory_ids)}).\"\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                try:\n                    uids = [UUID(i) for i in memory_ids]\n                except ValueError as e:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", f\"invalid UUID in memory_ids — {e}\"), t0\n                    )\n                # Trust gate (>= 3), mirroring single delete / REST DELETE. Blocks\n                # the cross-fleet bulk-delete-by-id IDOR for sub-admin agents; a\n                # trust>=3 admin agent retains tenant-wide delete (parity with\n                # enforce_fleet_write). No-op for tenant-scoped credentials.\n                if caller_agent_id:\n                    await enforce_delete(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id)\n                from datetime import UTC\n                from datetime import datetime as _dt\n\n                from sqlalchemy import update as _sa_update\n\n                from common.models.memory import Memory as _Mem\n\n                stmt = (\n                    _sa_update(_Mem)\n                    .where(\n                        _Mem.tenant_id == tenant_id,\n                        _Mem.id.in_(uids),\n                        _Mem.deleted_at.is_(None),\n                    )\n                    .values(deleted_at=_dt.now(UTC), status=\"deleted\")\n                )\n                result = await db.execute(stmt)\n                await log_action(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    agent_id=agent_id,\n                    action=\"bulk_delete\",\n                    resource_type=\"memory\",\n                    detail={\"count\": result.rowcount, \"method\": \"by_ids\", \"via\": \"mcp\"},\n                )\n                await db.commit()\n                return _with_latency(json.dumps({\"deleted\": result.rowcount, \"requested\": len(uids)}), t0)\n            if op == \"lineage\":\n                from sqlalchemy import select as _sa_select\n\n                from common.models.memory import Memory as _Mem\n\n                this = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n                if not this:\n                    return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n                # Fleet/agent-scope authorization (mirrors op=read): the\n                # supersession chain would otherwise leak a scoped row by id.\n                if not await authorize_memory_access(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id,\n                    caller_agent_id,\n                    visibility=this.visibility,\n                    owner_agent_id=this.agent_id,\n                    fleet_id=this.fleet_id,\n                ):\n                    return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n\n                # The older memory this row replaced (if any). The\n                # supersedes_id field points at the OLDER row (the\n                # detector's \"loser\"); this row was the winner.\n                superseded_by = None\n                if this.supersedes_id:\n                    older = await db.get(_Mem, this.supersedes_id)\n                    if older and older.tenant_id == tenant_id and older.deleted_at is None:\n                        superseded_by = {\n                            \"id\": str(older.id),\n                            \"content_preview\": older.content[:200],\n                            \"status\": older.status,\n                            \"created_at\": (older.created_at.isoformat() if older.created_at else None),\n                        }\n\n                # Newer rows whose supersedes_id points at this row\n                # (this row was their \"loser\").\n                stmt = (\n                    _sa_select(_Mem)\n                    .where(\n                        _Mem.supersedes_id == uid,\n                        _Mem.tenant_id == tenant_id,\n                        _Mem.deleted_at.is_(None),\n                    )\n                    .order_by(_Mem.created_at.desc())\n                )\n                supersessors = [\n                    {\n                        \"id\": str(m.id),\n                        \"content_preview\": m.content[:200],\n                        \"status\": m.status,\n                        \"created_at\": m.created_at.isoformat() if m.created_at else None,\n                    }\n                    for m in (await db.execute(stmt)).scalars().all()\n                ]\n                return _with_latency(\n                    json.dumps(\n                        {\n                            \"this\": {\n                                \"id\": str(this.id),\n                                \"status\": this.status,\n                                \"supersedes_id\": (str(this.supersedes_id) if this.supersedes_id else None),\n                            },\n                            \"superseded_by\": superseded_by,  # the OLDER row this replaced\n                            \"supersessors\": supersessors,  # NEWER rows that replaced this\n                        },\n                        default=str,\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            if op == \"read\":\n                memory = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n                if not memory:\n                    return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n                # Fleet/agent-scope authorization: honor the same scope_agent +\n                # cross-fleet trust ladder the search/list paths enforce, so an\n                # agent can't read a peer's scoped row by id. NOT_FOUND (not\n                # PERMISSION_DENIED) to avoid confirming the id exists.\n                if not await authorize_memory_access(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id,\n                    caller_agent_id,\n                    visibility=memory.visibility,\n                    owner_agent_id=memory.agent_id,\n                    fleet_id=memory.fleet_id,\n                ):\n                    return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n                return _with_latency(\n                    json.dumps(\n                        {\n                            \"id\": str(memory.id),\n                            \"content\": memory.content,\n                            \"memory_type\": memory.memory_type,\n                            \"status\": memory.status,\n                            \"weight\": memory.weight,\n                            \"agent_id\": memory.agent_id,\n                            \"fleet_id\": memory.fleet_id,\n                            \"visibility\": memory.visibility,\n                            \"title\": getattr(memory, \"title\", None),\n                            \"created_at\": memory.created_at.isoformat() if memory.created_at else None,\n                            \"last_recalled_at\": (\n                                memory.last_recalled_at.isoformat()\n                                if getattr(memory, \"last_recalled_at\", None)\n                                else None\n                            ),\n                            \"recall_count\": getattr(memory, \"recall_count\", 0),\n                            \"deleted_at\": (\n                                memory.deleted_at.isoformat() if getattr(memory, \"deleted_at\", None) else None\n                            ),\n                            \"metadata\": getattr(memory, \"metadata_\", None),\n                        },\n                        default=str,\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            if op == \"transition\":\n                if not status:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=transition requires 'status'.\"), t0\n                    )\n                if status not in MEMORY_STATUSES:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n                            f\"Invalid status '{status}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(MEMORY_STATUSES)}\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                memory = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n                if not memory:\n                    return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", \"Memory not found.\"), t0)\n                # Cross-fleet / scope_agent authorization (write threshold).\n                if not await authorize_memory_access(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id,\n                    caller_agent_id,\n                    visibility=memory.visibility,\n                    owner_agent_id=memory.agent_id,\n                    fleet_id=memory.fleet_id,\n                    write=True,\n                ):\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"PERMISSION_DENIED\",\n                            f\"Agent cannot modify memory in fleet '{memory.fleet_id}'.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                old_status = memory.status\n                await memory_repo.update_status(db, uid, status)\n                await log_action(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    agent_id=memory.agent_id,\n                    action=\"status_update\",\n                    resource_type=\"memory\",\n                    resource_id=uid,\n                    detail={\"old_status\": old_status, \"new_status\": status},\n                )\n                await db.commit()\n                return _with_latency(f\"Memory {memory_id} status updated: {old_status} -> {status}\", t0)\n            if op == \"update\":\n                fields: dict = {}\n                if content is not None:\n                    fields[\"content\"] = content\n                if memory_type is not None:\n                    fields[\"memory_type\"] = memory_type\n                if weight is not None:\n                    fields[\"weight\"] = weight\n                if title is not None:\n                    fields[\"title\"] = title\n                if status is not None:\n                    fields[\"status\"] = status\n                if metadata is not None:\n                    fields[\"metadata\"] = metadata\n                if source_uri is not None:\n                    fields[\"source_uri\"] = source_uri\n                if not fields:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n                            \"No fields to update. Provide at least one field to change.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n                result = await update_memory(db, uid, tenant_id, MemoryUpdate(**fields), agent_id=agent_id)\n                return _with_latency(_serialize(result), t0)\n            # op == \"delete\"\n            if caller_agent_id:\n                # Trust gate (>= 3) + cross-fleet / scope_agent row authorization,\n                # mirroring REST DELETE /memories/{id}.\n                await enforce_delete(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id)\n                target = await memory_repo.get_by_id_for_tenant(db, uid, tenant_id)\n                if target and not await authorize_memory_access(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id,\n                    caller_agent_id,\n                    visibility=target.visibility,\n                    owner_agent_id=target.agent_id,\n                    fleet_id=target.fleet_id,\n                    write=True,\n                ):\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"PERMISSION_DENIED\",\n                            f\"Agent cannot delete memory in fleet '{target.fleet_id}'.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n            await soft_delete_memory(db, uid, tenant_id)\n            return _with_latency(f\"Memory {memory_id} deleted.\", t0)\n        except HTTPException as e:\n            logger.warning(\"MCP tool error (%s): %s\", e.status_code, e.detail)\n            return _with_latency(_error_response(code_for_status(e.status_code), str(e.detail)), t0)\n\n\nasync def memclaw_entity_get(\n    entity_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"The UUID of the entity to look up.\")],\n) -> str:\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n    if err := _check_auth():\n        return err","lineStart":735,"lineEnd":1079,"totalLines":2542,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","time":{"start":1780729360406,"end":1780729360416}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055aada8abc9d1d5016a23c61055288191986e5960bf663315"}},"id":"prt_e9bbdb013001zhg2ku4K8YVBBT","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbd8857001Jxpg3QelvxEs1Q"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729360420,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_8YQDmkfkbvktKr1yl8Psqbvn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","offset":1169,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1169: async def memclaw_doc(\n1170:     op: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"write|read|query|delete|list_collections|search.\")],\n1171:     collection: Annotated[\n1172:         str | None,\n1173:         Field(\n1174:             description=\"Collection. Required for write|read|query|delete|search; omitted for list_collections.\"\n1175:         ),\n1176:     ] = None,\n1177:     doc_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=write|read|delete.\")] = None,\n1178:     data: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=write.\")] = None,\n1179:     where: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = None,\n1180:     order_by: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = None,\n1181:     order: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"op=query: asc|desc.\")] = \"asc\",\n1182:     limit: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = 20,\n1183:     offset: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = 0,\n1184:     agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n1185:     fleet_id: Annotated[\n1186:         str | None,\n1187:         Field(description=\"op=write; optional scoping filter for op=list_collections|search.\"),\n1188:     ] = None,\n1189:     query: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=search: natural-language query.\")] = None,\n1190:     top_k: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=search: max results (1-50).\")] = 5,\n1191: ) -> str:\n1192:     \"\"\"Structured-document CRUD. Op-dispatched. Replaces the 4 prior\n1193:     `memclaw_doc_*` tools.\"\"\"\n1194:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n1195:     if err := _check_auth():\n1196:         return err\n1197:     _valid_ops = {\"write\", \"read\", \"query\", \"delete\", \"list_collections\", \"search\"}\n1198:     if op not in _valid_ops:\n1199:         return _with_latency(\n1200:             json.dumps(\n1201:                 {\n1202:                     \"error\": {\n1203:                         \"code\": \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n1204:                         \"message\": f\"Unknown op '{op}'. Expected one of: {sorted(_valid_ops)}.\",\n1205:                         \"details\": {\"op\": op, \"expected_ops\": sorted(_valid_ops)},\n1206:                     }\n1207:                 }\n1208:             ),\n1209:             t0,\n1210:         )\n1211:     # `collection` is required for write/read/query/delete. It is optional\n1212:     # for list_collections (by design) and for search (where omitting it\n1213:     # means \"search across every collection in this tenant\" — the broad\n1214:     # strategy; supply collection to scope the search to just one).\n1215:     if op not in {\"list_collections\", \"search\"} and not collection:\n1216:         return _with_latency(_error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", f\"op={op} requires 'collection'.\"), t0)\n1217:     # Write/delete are gated by the credential scope set; read/query/list/search\n1218:     # remain available to read-only keys.\n1219:     if op in {\"write\", \"delete\"} and (err := _check_write_scope()):\n1220:         return err\n1221:     tenant_id = _get_tenant()\n1222:     # Raw authenticated identity for the delete trust gate (None ⇒ no agent\n1223:     # context). Must not fall back to the ``mcp-agent`` default.\n1224:     caller_agent_id = _get_agent_id()\n1225:     agent_id = caller_agent_id or agent_id\n1226:     # A29 — refuse the default identity on every op. Was previously\n1227:     # write-only (A14); reads inherit the same contract because the\n1228:     # silent-empty-result UX is its own class of paper cut, and ``delete``\n1229:     # is a destructive op that was inadvertently un-guarded under the\n1230:     # earlier write-only scope.\n1231:     if refuse := _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id):\n1232:         return _with_latency(refuse, t0)\n1233: \n1234:     from core_api.repositories import document_repo\n1235: \n1236:     # Cross-tenant credentials widen read ops (list_collections, read,\n1237:     # query, search) via ``readable_tenant_ids``. Write/delete pin to\n1238:     # home_tenant — same contract as recall vs write. ``readable``\n1239:     # stays None for single-tenant callers; document_repo falls back to\n1240:     # ``tenant_id = $1``.\n1241:     readable = _get_readable_tenants() or None\n1242:     READ_OPS = {\"list_collections\", \"read\", \"query\", \"search\"}\n1243: \n1244:     async with _mcp_session() as db:\n1245:         try:\n1246:             if op == \"list_collections\":\n1247:                 rows = await document_repo.list_collections(\n1248:                     db,\n1249:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n1250:                     fleet_id=fleet_id,\n1251:                     readable_tenant_ids=readable if op in READ_OPS else None,\n1252:                 )\n1253:                 return _with_latency(\n1254:                     json.dumps(\n1255:                         {\n1256:                             \"collections\": [{\"name\": name, \"count\": count} for name, count in rows],\n1257:                             \"count\": len(rows),\n1258:                         }\n1259:                     ),\n1260:                     t0,\n1261:                 )\n1262:             if op == \"write\":\n1263:                 if not doc_id:\n1264:                     return _with_latency(\n1265:                         _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=write requires 'doc_id'.\"), t0\n1266:                     )\n1267:                 if data is None:\n1268:                     return _with_latency(\n1269:                         _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=write requires 'data'.\"), t0\n1270:                     )\n1271:                 # Skills slug rule — doc_id becomes a filesystem directory\n1272:                 # on the plugin side, so it must be filesystem-safe.\n1273:                 if collection == SKILLS_COLLECTION and not _SKILL_SLUG_RE.fullmatch(doc_id):\n1274:                     return _with_latency(\n1275:                         _error_response(\n1276:                             \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n1277:                             f\"collection='skills' requires doc_id matching \"\n1278:                             f\"{_SKILL_SLUG_RE.pattern} — got {doc_id!r}. \"\n1279:                             \"Slugs become directory names on each plugin node.\",\n1280:                         ),\n1281:                         t0,\n1282:                     )\n1283:                 # Resolve which string in `data` gets embedded. The only\n1284:                 # embeddable field is data[\"summary\"]; skills writes also\n1285:                 # accept data[\"description\"] for back-compat. Non-skills\n1286:                 # writes without a summary store cleanly with no embedding\n1287:                 # (doc won't appear in op=search).\n1288:                 from core_api.services.doc_indexing import (\n1289:                     InvalidDocIndexingError,\n1290:                     resolve_embed_source,\n1291:                 )\n1292: \n1293:                 try:\n1294:                     source = resolve_embed_source(collection, data)\n1295:                 except InvalidDocIndexingError as exc:\n1296:                     return _with_latency(_error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", str(exc)), t0)\n1297:                 embedding: list[float] | None = None\n1298:                 if source is not None:\n1299:                     from common.embedding import get_embedding\n1300: \n1301:                     embedding = await get_embedding(source)\n1302:                     if embedding is None:\n1303:                         return _with_latency(\n1304:                             _error_response(\n1305:                                 \"UPSTREAM_ERROR\",\n1306:                                 \"Embedding provider returned no vector \"\n1307:                                 \"(check provider config / quota). Write aborted.\",\n1308:                             ),\n1309:                             t0,\n1310:                         )\n1311:                 # Mirror memclaw_write's agent registration so a doc upsert\n1312:                 # via MCP creates the Agent row on first contact and enforces\n1313:                 # cross-fleet trust gating.\n1314:                 await enforce_fleet_write(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id)\n1315:                 await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n1316:                 row = await document_repo.upsert_returning_xmax(\n1317:                     db,\n1318:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n1319:                     fleet_id=fleet_id,\n1320:                     collection=collection,\n1321:                     doc_id=doc_id,\n1322:                     data=data,\n1323:                     embedding=embedding,\n1324:                 )\n1325:                 if row is None:\n1326:                     return _with_latency(\n1327:                         _error_response(\"INTERNAL_ERROR\", \"document upsert returned no rows\"), t0\n1328:                     )\n1329:                 await db.commit()\n1330:                 # `text(\"xmax\")` is unlabeled in SQLAlchemy ≥ 2; access by\n1331:                 # tuple position. Returning columns are: id, created_at,\n1332:                 # updated_at, xmax — so xmax sits at index 3.\n1333:                 is_new = int(row[3]) == 0\n1334:                 return _with_latency(\n1335:                     json.dumps(\n1336:                         {\n1337:                             \"ok\": True,\n1338:                             \"collection\": collection,\n1339:                             \"doc_id\": doc_id,\n1340:                             \"action\": \"created\" if is_new else \"updated\",\n1341:                             \"indexed\": embedding is not None,\n1342:                         }\n1343:                     ),\n1344:                     t0,\n1345:                 )\n1346:             if op == \"read\":\n1347:                 if not doc_id:\n1348:                     return _with_latency(\n1349:                         _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=read requires 'doc_id'.\"), t0\n1350:                     )\n1351:                 doc = await document_repo.get_by_doc_id(\n1352:                     db,\n1353:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n1354:                     collection=collection,\n1355:                     doc_id=doc_id,\n1356:                     readable_tenant_ids=readable,\n1357:                 )\n1358:                 if not doc:\n1359:                     return _with_latency(f\"Not found: {collection}/{doc_id}\", t0)\n1360:                 return _with_latency(\n1361:                     json.dumps(\n1362:                         {\n1363:                             \"collection\": doc.collection,\n1364:                             \"doc_id\": doc.doc_id,\n1365:                             \"data\": doc.data,\n1366:                             \"updated_at\": doc.updated_at.isoformat(),\n1367:                         },\n1368:                         default=str,\n1369:                     ),\n1370:                     t0,\n1371:                 )\n1372:             if op == \"query\":\n1373:                 docs = await document_repo.query(\n1374:                     db,\n1375:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n1376:                     collection=collection,\n1377:                     where=where or {},\n1378:                     order_by=order_by,\n1379:                     order=order,\n1380:                     limit=min(limit, 100),\n1381:                     offset=offset,\n1382:                     readable_tenant_ids=readable,\n1383:                 )\n1384:                 items = [{\"doc_id\": d.doc_id, \"data\": d.data} for d in docs]\n1385:                 return _with_latency(\n1386:                     json.dumps(\n1387:                         {\"collection\": collection, \"count\": len(items), \"results\": items},\n1388:                         default=str,\n1389:                     ),\n1390:                     t0,\n1391:                 )\n1392:             if op == \"search\":\n1393:                 if not query or not query.strip():\n1394:                     return _with_latency(\n1395:                         _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=search requires a non-empty 'query'.\"), t0\n1396:                     )\n1397:                 from common.embedding import get_embedding\n1398: \n1399:                 query_embedding = await get_embedding(query)\n1400:                 if query_embedding is None:\n1401:                     return _with_latency(\n1402:                         _error_response(\n1403:                             \"UPSTREAM_ERROR\",\n1404:                             \"Embedding provider returned no vector \"\n1405:                             \"(check provider config / quota). Search aborted.\",\n1406:                         ),\n1407:                         t0,\n1408:                     )\n1409:                 capped_top_k = max(1, min(top_k, 50))\n1410:                 pairs = await document_repo.search(\n1411:                     db,\n1412:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n1413:                     collection=collection,  # None = span every collection (broad)\n1414:                     query_embedding=query_embedding,\n1415:                     top_k=capped_top_k,\n1416:                     fleet_id=fleet_id,\n1417:                     readable_tenant_ids=readable,\n1418:                 )\n1419:                 source_tenants = [t for t in (readable or []) if t and t != tenant_id]\n1420:                 if source_tenants:\n1421:                     counts: dict[str, int] = {}\n1422:                     for d, _sim in pairs:\n1423:                         rt = getattr(d, \"tenant_id\", None)\n1424:                         if rt:\n1425:                             counts[rt] = counts.get(rt, 0) + 1\n1426:                     await log_cross_tenant_read(\n1427:                         db,\n1428:                         home_tenant_id=tenant_id,\n\n(Showing lines 1169-1428 of 2542. Use offset=1429 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"async def memclaw_doc(\n    op: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"write|read|query|delete|list_collections|search.\")],\n    collection: Annotated[\n        str | None,\n        Field(\n            description=\"Collection. Required for write|read|query|delete|search; omitted for list_collections.\"\n        ),\n    ] = None,\n    doc_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=write|read|delete.\")] = None,\n    data: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=write.\")] = None,\n    where: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = None,\n    order_by: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = None,\n    order: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"op=query: asc|desc.\")] = \"asc\",\n    limit: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = 20,\n    offset: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = 0,\n    agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n    fleet_id: Annotated[\n        str | None,\n        Field(description=\"op=write; optional scoping filter for op=list_collections|search.\"),\n    ] = None,","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","text":"async def memclaw_doc(\n    op: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"write|read|query|delete|list_collections|search.\")],\n    collection: Annotated[\n        str | None,\n        Field(\n            description=\"Collection. Required for write|read|query|delete|search; omitted for list_collections.\"\n        ),\n    ] = None,\n    doc_id: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=write|read|delete.\")] = None,\n    data: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=write.\")] = None,\n    where: Annotated[dict | None, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = None,\n    order_by: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = None,\n    order: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"op=query: asc|desc.\")] = \"asc\",\n    limit: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = 20,\n    offset: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=query.\")] = 0,\n    agent_id: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"Caller agent.\")] = \"mcp-agent\",\n    fleet_id: Annotated[\n        str | None,\n        Field(description=\"op=write; optional scoping filter for op=list_collections|search.\"),\n    ] = None,\n    query: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=search: natural-language query.\")] = None,\n    top_k: Annotated[int, Field(description=\"op=search: max results (1-50).\")] = 5,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Structured-document CRUD. Op-dispatched. Replaces the 4 prior\n    `memclaw_doc_*` tools.\"\"\"\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n    if err := _check_auth():\n        return err\n    _valid_ops = {\"write\", \"read\", \"query\", \"delete\", \"list_collections\", \"search\"}\n    if op not in _valid_ops:\n        return _with_latency(\n            json.dumps(\n                {\n                    \"error\": {\n                        \"code\": \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n                        \"message\": f\"Unknown op '{op}'. Expected one of: {sorted(_valid_ops)}.\",\n                        \"details\": {\"op\": op, \"expected_ops\": sorted(_valid_ops)},\n                    }\n                }\n            ),\n            t0,\n        )\n    # `collection` is required for write/read/query/delete. It is optional\n    # for list_collections (by design) and for search (where omitting it\n    # means \"search across every collection in this tenant\" — the broad\n    # strategy; supply collection to scope the search to just one).\n    if op not in {\"list_collections\", \"search\"} and not collection:\n        return _with_latency(_error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", f\"op={op} requires 'collection'.\"), t0)\n    # Write/delete are gated by the credential scope set; read/query/list/search\n    # remain available to read-only keys.\n    if op in {\"write\", \"delete\"} and (err := _check_write_scope()):\n        return err\n    tenant_id = _get_tenant()\n    # Raw authenticated identity for the delete trust gate (None ⇒ no agent\n    # context). Must not fall back to the ``mcp-agent`` default.\n    caller_agent_id = _get_agent_id()\n    agent_id = caller_agent_id or agent_id\n    # A29 — refuse the default identity on every op. Was previously\n    # write-only (A14); reads inherit the same contract because the\n    # silent-empty-result UX is its own class of paper cut, and ``delete``\n    # is a destructive op that was inadvertently un-guarded under the\n    # earlier write-only scope.\n    if refuse := _refuse_default_agent_on_gateway(agent_id):\n        return _with_latency(refuse, t0)\n\n    from core_api.repositories import document_repo\n\n    # Cross-tenant credentials widen read ops (list_collections, read,\n    # query, search) via ``readable_tenant_ids``. Write/delete pin to\n    # home_tenant — same contract as recall vs write. ``readable``\n    # stays None for single-tenant callers; document_repo falls back to\n    # ``tenant_id = $1``.\n    readable = _get_readable_tenants() or None\n    READ_OPS = {\"list_collections\", \"read\", \"query\", \"search\"}\n\n    async with _mcp_session() as db:\n        try:\n            if op == \"list_collections\":\n                rows = await document_repo.list_collections(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    fleet_id=fleet_id,\n                    readable_tenant_ids=readable if op in READ_OPS else None,\n                )\n                return _with_latency(\n                    json.dumps(\n                        {\n                            \"collections\": [{\"name\": name, \"count\": count} for name, count in rows],\n                            \"count\": len(rows),\n                        }\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            if op == \"write\":\n                if not doc_id:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=write requires 'doc_id'.\"), t0\n                    )\n                if data is None:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=write requires 'data'.\"), t0\n                    )\n                # Skills slug rule — doc_id becomes a filesystem directory\n                # on the plugin side, so it must be filesystem-safe.\n                if collection == SKILLS_COLLECTION and not _SKILL_SLUG_RE.fullmatch(doc_id):\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\",\n                            f\"collection='skills' requires doc_id matching \"\n                            f\"{_SKILL_SLUG_RE.pattern} — got {doc_id!r}. \"\n                            \"Slugs become directory names on each plugin node.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                # Resolve which string in `data` gets embedded. The only\n                # embeddable field is data[\"summary\"]; skills writes also\n                # accept data[\"description\"] for back-compat. Non-skills\n                # writes without a summary store cleanly with no embedding\n                # (doc won't appear in op=search).\n                from core_api.services.doc_indexing import (\n                    InvalidDocIndexingError,\n                    resolve_embed_source,\n                )\n\n                try:\n                    source = resolve_embed_source(collection, data)\n                except InvalidDocIndexingError as exc:\n                    return _with_latency(_error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", str(exc)), t0)\n                embedding: list[float] | None = None\n                if source is not None:\n                    from common.embedding import get_embedding\n\n                    embedding = await get_embedding(source)\n                    if embedding is None:\n                        return _with_latency(\n                            _error_response(\n                                \"UPSTREAM_ERROR\",\n                                \"Embedding provider returned no vector \"\n                                \"(check provider config / quota). Write aborted.\",\n                            ),\n                            t0,\n                        )\n                # Mirror memclaw_write's agent registration so a doc upsert\n                # via MCP creates the Agent row on first contact and enforces\n                # cross-fleet trust gating.\n                await enforce_fleet_write(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id)\n                await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n                row = await document_repo.upsert_returning_xmax(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    fleet_id=fleet_id,\n                    collection=collection,\n                    doc_id=doc_id,\n                    data=data,\n                    embedding=embedding,\n                )\n                if row is None:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\"INTERNAL_ERROR\", \"document upsert returned no rows\"), t0\n                    )\n                await db.commit()\n                # `text(\"xmax\")` is unlabeled in SQLAlchemy ≥ 2; access by\n                # tuple position. Returning columns are: id, created_at,\n                # updated_at, xmax — so xmax sits at index 3.\n                is_new = int(row[3]) == 0\n                return _with_latency(\n                    json.dumps(\n                        {\n                            \"ok\": True,\n                            \"collection\": collection,\n                            \"doc_id\": doc_id,\n                            \"action\": \"created\" if is_new else \"updated\",\n                            \"indexed\": embedding is not None,\n                        }\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            if op == \"read\":\n                if not doc_id:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=read requires 'doc_id'.\"), t0\n                    )\n                doc = await document_repo.get_by_doc_id(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    collection=collection,\n                    doc_id=doc_id,\n                    readable_tenant_ids=readable,\n                )\n                if not doc:\n                    return _with_latency(f\"Not found: {collection}/{doc_id}\", t0)\n                return _with_latency(\n                    json.dumps(\n                        {\n                            \"collection\": doc.collection,\n                            \"doc_id\": doc.doc_id,\n                            \"data\": doc.data,\n                            \"updated_at\": doc.updated_at.isoformat(),\n                        },\n                        default=str,\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            if op == \"query\":\n                docs = await document_repo.query(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    collection=collection,\n                    where=where or {},\n                    order_by=order_by,\n                    order=order,\n                    limit=min(limit, 100),\n                    offset=offset,\n                    readable_tenant_ids=readable,\n                )\n                items = [{\"doc_id\": d.doc_id, \"data\": d.data} for d in docs]\n                return _with_latency(\n                    json.dumps(\n                        {\"collection\": collection, \"count\": len(items), \"results\": items},\n                        default=str,\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            if op == \"search\":\n                if not query or not query.strip():\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\"INVALID_ARGUMENTS\", \"op=search requires a non-empty 'query'.\"), t0\n                    )\n                from common.embedding import get_embedding\n\n                query_embedding = await get_embedding(query)\n                if query_embedding is None:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"UPSTREAM_ERROR\",\n                            \"Embedding provider returned no vector \"\n                            \"(check provider config / quota). Search aborted.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                capped_top_k = max(1, min(top_k, 50))\n                pairs = await document_repo.search(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    collection=collection,  # None = span every collection (broad)\n                    query_embedding=query_embedding,\n                    top_k=capped_top_k,\n                    fleet_id=fleet_id,\n                    readable_tenant_ids=readable,\n                )\n                source_tenants = [t for t in (readable or []) if t and t != tenant_id]\n                if source_tenants:\n                    counts: dict[str, int] = {}\n                    for d, _sim in pairs:\n                        rt = getattr(d, \"tenant_id\", None)\n                        if rt:\n                            counts[rt] = counts.get(rt, 0) + 1\n                    await log_cross_tenant_read(\n                        db,\n                        home_tenant_id=tenant_id,","lineStart":1169,"lineEnd":1428,"totalLines":2542,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","time":{"start":1780729360412,"end":1780729360419}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055aada8abc9d1d5016a23c61055348191bf30ba5d777d617a"}},"id":"prt_e9bbdb0170012HfRWhAYRRT6eg","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbd8857001Jxpg3QelvxEs1Q"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729360438,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_z9chv0uPRAJCeKwcfBDf71cp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/AGENT-INSTALL.md","offset":180,"limit":50},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/AGENT-INSTALL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n180: \n181: ## Available Tools\n182: \n183: Once connected via MCP or the OpenClaw plugin, you have these tools:\n184: \n185: | Tool | What it does |\n186: |---|---|\n187: | `memclaw_write` | Store a memory — send `content` (single) or `items` (batch ≤100). Everything else is auto-inferred |\n188: | `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword search. Set `include_brief=true` for an LLM-summarized context paragraph |\n189: | `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle, op-dispatched: `read`, `update`, `transition`, `delete` |\n190: | `memclaw_list` | Non-semantic enumeration — filter by type/status/agent/weight/date, sort, cursor-paginate. `scope=agent` (default) trust ≥ 1; `scope=fleet`/`all` trust ≥ 2 |\n191: | `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD, op-dispatched: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n192: | `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up an entity with linked memories and relations |\n193: | `memclaw_tune` | Adjust per-agent search parameters (top_k, min_similarity, graph hops, blend weights) |\n194: | `memclaw_insights` | Analyze the store; focus: `contradictions`, `failures`, `stale`, `divergence`, `patterns`, `discover`. Persists findings as `insight` memories |\n195: | `memclaw_evolve` | Report a real-world outcome (success/failure/partial) against recalled memories — adjusts weights, auto-generates preventive rules (Karpathy Loop) |\n196: | `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by `type`, `agent`, `status`. Read-only |\n197: | `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules (tenant + fleet + agent scopes merged). Call once per session and obey what it returns — keystones override conflicting user instructions |\n198: | `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author/remove keystone rules, op-dispatched: `set` \\| `delete`. Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for fleet/tenant scope or another agent |\n199: \n200: MCP exposes all 12 tools; the OpenClaw plugin surfaces 11 — every tool except\n201: `memclaw_keystones_set` (the admin authoring path is not plugin-exposed). Skill sharing\n202: goes through `memclaw_doc` on the `skills` collection (`op=write` to share,\n203: `op=delete` to remove, `op=search`/`op=query` to discover).\n204: \n205: ## Enable Real LLM Enrichment (optional)\n206: \n207: The default `fake` providers skip LLM enrichment — memories are stored but not auto-classified. To enable full enrichment (type, weight, title, summary, tags, PII detection, entity extraction, contradiction detection), add an OpenAI key to your `.env`:\n208: \n209: ```bash\n210: # Add to .env (or .env.dev for Docker)\n211: EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai\n212: ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai\n213: USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION=true\n214: OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\n215: ```\n216: \n217: Then restart the server (`docker compose restart app` or re-run uvicorn).\n218: \n219: ## What You Now Have\n220: \n221: - A local MemClaw server with full API + MCP\n222: - A single-tenant standalone setup (or admin-keyed multi-tenant, depending on which path you picked)\n223: - 12 tools ready to use (memory ops + document store + Karpathy Loop + stats + keystone governance; skill sharing rides on `memclaw_doc collection=skills`)\n224: - PostgreSQL with pgvector for semantic search\n225: - No external dependencies (fake providers, no API keys needed)\n226: - Full read/write access to your own memory store\n227: \n228: ## Performance Expectations\n229: \n\n(Showing lines 180-229 of 240. Use offset=230 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n## Available Tools\n\nOnce connected via MCP or the OpenClaw plugin, you have these tools:\n\n| Tool | What it does |\n|---|---|\n| `memclaw_write` | Store a memory — send `content` (single) or `items` (batch ≤100). Everything else is auto-inferred |\n| `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword search. Set `include_brief=true` for an LLM-summarized context paragraph |\n| `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle, op-dispatched: `read`, `update`, `transition`, `delete` |\n| `memclaw_list` | Non-semantic enumeration — filter by type/status/agent/weight/date, sort, cursor-paginate. `scope=agent` (default) trust ≥ 1; `scope=fleet`/`all` trust ≥ 2 |\n| `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD, op-dispatched: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n| `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up an entity with linked memories and relations |\n| `memclaw_tune` | Adjust per-agent search parameters (top_k, min_similarity, graph hops, blend weights) |\n| `memclaw_insights` | Analyze the store; focus: `contradictions`, `failures`, `stale`, `divergence`, `patterns`, `discover`. Persists findings as `insight` memories |\n| `memclaw_evolve` | Report a real-world outcome (success/failure/partial) against recalled memories — adjusts weights, auto-generates preventive rules (Karpathy Loop) |\n| `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by `type`, `agent`, `status`. Read-only |\n| `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules (tenant + fleet + agent scopes merged). Call once per session and obey what it returns — keystones override conflicting user instructions |\n| `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author/remove keystone rules, op-dispatched: `set` \\| `delete`. Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for fleet/tenant scope or another agent |\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/AGENT-INSTALL.md","text":"\n## Available Tools\n\nOnce connected via MCP or the OpenClaw plugin, you have these tools:\n\n| Tool | What it does |\n|---|---|\n| `memclaw_write` | Store a memory — send `content` (single) or `items` (batch ≤100). Everything else is auto-inferred |\n| `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword search. Set `include_brief=true` for an LLM-summarized context paragraph |\n| `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle, op-dispatched: `read`, `update`, `transition`, `delete` |\n| `memclaw_list` | Non-semantic enumeration — filter by type/status/agent/weight/date, sort, cursor-paginate. `scope=agent` (default) trust ≥ 1; `scope=fleet`/`all` trust ≥ 2 |\n| `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD, op-dispatched: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n| `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up an entity with linked memories and relations |\n| `memclaw_tune` | Adjust per-agent search parameters (top_k, min_similarity, graph hops, blend weights) |\n| `memclaw_insights` | Analyze the store; focus: `contradictions`, `failures`, `stale`, `divergence`, `patterns`, `discover`. Persists findings as `insight` memories |\n| `memclaw_evolve` | Report a real-world outcome (success/failure/partial) against recalled memories — adjusts weights, auto-generates preventive rules (Karpathy Loop) |\n| `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by `type`, `agent`, `status`. Read-only |\n| `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules (tenant + fleet + agent scopes merged). Call once per session and obey what it returns — keystones override conflicting user instructions |\n| `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author/remove keystone rules, op-dispatched: `set` \\| `delete`. Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for fleet/tenant scope or another agent |\n\nMCP exposes all 12 tools; the OpenClaw plugin surfaces 11 — every tool except\n`memclaw_keystones_set` (the admin authoring path is not plugin-exposed). Skill sharing\ngoes through `memclaw_doc` on the `skills` collection (`op=write` to share,\n`op=delete` to remove, `op=search`/`op=query` to discover).\n\n## Enable Real LLM Enrichment (optional)\n\nThe default `fake` providers skip LLM enrichment — memories are stored but not auto-classified. To enable full enrichment (type, weight, title, summary, tags, PII detection, entity extraction, contradiction detection), add an OpenAI key to your `.env`:\n\n```bash\n# Add to .env (or .env.dev for Docker)\nEMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai\nENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai\nUSE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION=true\nOPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\n```\n\nThen restart the server (`docker compose restart app` or re-run uvicorn).\n\n## What You Now Have\n\n- A local MemClaw server with full API + MCP\n- A single-tenant standalone setup (or admin-keyed multi-tenant, depending on which path you picked)\n- 12 tools ready to use (memory ops + document store + Karpathy Loop + stats + keystone governance; skill sharing rides on `memclaw_doc collection=skills`)\n- PostgreSQL with pgvector for semantic search\n- No external dependencies (fake providers, no API keys needed)\n- Full read/write access to your own memory store\n\n## Performance Expectations\n","lineStart":180,"lineEnd":229,"totalLines":240,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/AGENT-INSTALL.md","time":{"start":1780729360435,"end":1780729360438}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055aada8abc9d1d5016a23c610553c8191b2c4a6e8989c2161"}},"id":"prt_e9bbdb01d0017IFdPF2rMCuDMI","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbd8857001Jxpg3QelvxEs1Q"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729360453,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_1KUWKjXsu6qtPyB8p6wjdor0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/CONTRIBUTING.md","offset":1,"limit":140},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/CONTRIBUTING.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Contributing to MemClaw\n2: \n3: Thanks for your interest in contributing! This document covers how to get set\n4: up, the expected workflow, and how we review changes.\n5: \n6: ## Ground Rules\n7: \n8: - By contributing, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the\n9:   [Apache License 2.0](LICENSE).\n10: - **Sign off every commit** under the [Developer Certificate of Origin](https://developercertificate.org/) (DCO) — see \"Sign-off (DCO)\" below.\n11: - **Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/)** for commit subjects — see \"Commit messages\" below.\n12: - Be respectful. See our [Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md).\n13: - For security issues, see [SECURITY.md](SECURITY.md) — do not open a public\n14:   issue.\n15: \n16: ## Development Setup\n17: \n18: ### Prerequisites\n19: \n20: - Python 3.12+\n21: - PostgreSQL 16+ with the `pgvector` extension (or use Docker Compose)\n22: - Node.js 20+ (only if you're working on the `plugin/` directory)\n23: - `uv` (recommended) or `pip` for Python dependency management\n24: \n25: ### Clone and set up a venv\n26: \n27: ```bash\n28: git clone https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw.git\n29: cd caura-memclaw\n30: uv venv .venv\n31: source .venv/bin/activate\n32: uv pip install -e \"core-api/[dev]\" -e \"core-storage-api/[dev]\"\n33: ```\n34: \n35: ### Install the pre-commit hook\n36: \n37: One-time setup that makes every `git commit` run `ruff check` and\n38: `ruff format` — catches formatting regressions before they reach the PR:\n39: \n40: ```bash\n41: pip install pre-commit   # or: uv pip install pre-commit\n42: pre-commit install\n43: ```\n44: \n45: The hook is configured in `.pre-commit-config.yaml` and only runs against\n46: `core-api/src/` and `core-storage-api/src/`. `mypy` is intentionally not in\n47: the hook (it needs the real project venv to resolve workspace imports\n48: correctly) — CI runs it authoritatively, and you can run it locally via\n49: the command under \"Run local checks\" below.\n50: \n51: ### Run services locally\n52: \n53: The fastest path is Docker Compose:\n54: \n55: ```bash\n56: docker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml up -d\n57: ```\n58: \n59: This starts PostgreSQL + pgvector, Redis, and the core API with hot reload.\n60: \n61: ### Run the test suite\n62: \n63: ```bash\n64: pytest tests/ -v\n65: ```\n66: \n67: See `README.md` for more deployment options and environment variable details.\n68: \n69: ## Workflow\n70: \n71: 1. **Open an issue first** for anything non-trivial — a bug fix under ~30 lines\n72:    is fine to submit directly as a PR, but larger changes benefit from\n73:    discussion before code is written.\n74: 2. **Create a branch** from `main` with a short descriptive name (e.g. `feat/fleet-id-filter`, `fix/plugin-heartbeat`).\n75: 3. **Make your change.** Keep PRs focused — one logical change per PR.\n76: 4. **Add or update tests.** We don't accept new features without tests, and bug\n77:    fixes should include a regression test.\n78: 5. **Run local checks.** With the pre-commit hook installed, ruff check +\n79:    ruff format already ran on `git commit`, so you only need:\n80:    ```bash\n81:    mypy core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n82:    pytest tests/\n83:    ```\n84:    Without the hook, also run ruff by hand:\n85:    ```bash\n86:    ruff check core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n87:    ruff format --check core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n88:    mypy core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n89:    pytest tests/\n90:    ```\n91: 6. **Open a PR against `main`.** Fill out the PR template. Branch protection requires CI green, DCO check green, and ≥1 maintainer approval before merge.\n92: 7. **Respond to review.** Expect at least one round of feedback.\n93: \n94: ## Commit messages\n95: \n96: We use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/). The\n97: subject line must be `<type>(<optional-scope>): <subject>`, with the\n98: type drawn from this list:\n99: \n100: | Type | Effect on the next release |\n101: |---|---|\n102: | `feat` | Minor bump |\n103: | `fix` | Patch bump |\n104: | `perf` | Patch bump |\n105: | `deps` | Patch bump (auto-applied by Dependabot) |\n106: | `revert` | Patch bump |\n107: | `docs` | No release impact, surfaces in CHANGELOG |\n108: | `refactor` | No release impact, surfaces in CHANGELOG |\n109: | `test`, `build`, `ci`, `chore` | Hidden from CHANGELOG, no release impact |\n110: \n111: Append `!` (`feat!: …`) or a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer for changes\n112: that break the [Public API](README.md#public-api--stability) — these\n113: trigger a major bump once we ship 1.0.0. Before 1.0.0 they're treated\n114: as minor (`bump-minor-pre-major: true` in `release-please-config.json`).\n115: \n116: **Scopes** (optional but encouraged): `core-api`, `core-storage-api`,\n117: `core-worker`, `plugin`, `common`, `mcp`, `skill`, `e2e`, `benchmarks`,\n118: `docs`, `ci`.\n119: \n120: **Other rules:**\n121: \n122: - Subject line under 72 characters, imperative mood (\"add X\", not \"added X\").\n123: - Include context in the body when the change is non-obvious.\n124: - One logical change per commit.\n125: \n126: **Squash-merge note:** PR titles must themselves be Conventional Commits,\n127: because the squash-merge commit on `main` is what release-please reads.\n128: Reviewers will rename PR titles before merging if needed.\n129: \n130: ## Sign-off (DCO)\n131: \n132: Every commit must carry a `Signed-off-by:` trailer asserting the\n133: [Developer Certificate of Origin](https://developercertificate.org/) —\n134: a one-paragraph statement that you have the right to submit the work\n135: under the project's license. This is a lightweight alternative to a CLA\n136: and is what the Linux kernel, Docker, and GitLab use.\n137: \n138: Sign off automatically with `git commit -s`:\n139: \n140: ```bash\n\n(Showing lines 1-140 of 183. Use offset=141 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Contributing to MemClaw\n\nThanks for your interest in contributing! This document covers how to get set\nup, the expected workflow, and how we review changes.\n\n## Ground Rules\n\n- By contributing, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the\n  [Apache License 2.0](LICENSE).\n- **Sign off every commit** under the [Developer Certificate of Origin](https://developercertificate.org/) (DCO) — see \"Sign-off (DCO)\" below.\n- **Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/)** for commit subjects — see \"Commit messages\" below.\n- Be respectful. See our [Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md).\n- For security issues, see [SECURITY.md](SECURITY.md) — do not open a public\n  issue.\n\n## Development Setup\n\n### Prerequisites\n\n- Python 3.12+","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/CONTRIBUTING.md","text":"# Contributing to MemClaw\n\nThanks for your interest in contributing! This document covers how to get set\nup, the expected workflow, and how we review changes.\n\n## Ground Rules\n\n- By contributing, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under the\n  [Apache License 2.0](LICENSE).\n- **Sign off every commit** under the [Developer Certificate of Origin](https://developercertificate.org/) (DCO) — see \"Sign-off (DCO)\" below.\n- **Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/)** for commit subjects — see \"Commit messages\" below.\n- Be respectful. See our [Code of Conduct](CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md).\n- For security issues, see [SECURITY.md](SECURITY.md) — do not open a public\n  issue.\n\n## Development Setup\n\n### Prerequisites\n\n- Python 3.12+\n- PostgreSQL 16+ with the `pgvector` extension (or use Docker Compose)\n- Node.js 20+ (only if you're working on the `plugin/` directory)\n- `uv` (recommended) or `pip` for Python dependency management\n\n### Clone and set up a venv\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw.git\ncd caura-memclaw\nuv venv .venv\nsource .venv/bin/activate\nuv pip install -e \"core-api/[dev]\" -e \"core-storage-api/[dev]\"\n```\n\n### Install the pre-commit hook\n\nOne-time setup that makes every `git commit` run `ruff check` and\n`ruff format` — catches formatting regressions before they reach the PR:\n\n```bash\npip install pre-commit   # or: uv pip install pre-commit\npre-commit install\n```\n\nThe hook is configured in `.pre-commit-config.yaml` and only runs against\n`core-api/src/` and `core-storage-api/src/`. `mypy` is intentionally not in\nthe hook (it needs the real project venv to resolve workspace imports\ncorrectly) — CI runs it authoritatively, and you can run it locally via\nthe command under \"Run local checks\" below.\n\n### Run services locally\n\nThe fastest path is Docker Compose:\n\n```bash\ndocker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml up -d\n```\n\nThis starts PostgreSQL + pgvector, Redis, and the core API with hot reload.\n\n### Run the test suite\n\n```bash\npytest tests/ -v\n```\n\nSee `README.md` for more deployment options and environment variable details.\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Open an issue first** for anything non-trivial — a bug fix under ~30 lines\n   is fine to submit directly as a PR, but larger changes benefit from\n   discussion before code is written.\n2. **Create a branch** from `main` with a short descriptive name (e.g. `feat/fleet-id-filter`, `fix/plugin-heartbeat`).\n3. **Make your change.** Keep PRs focused — one logical change per PR.\n4. **Add or update tests.** We don't accept new features without tests, and bug\n   fixes should include a regression test.\n5. **Run local checks.** With the pre-commit hook installed, ruff check +\n   ruff format already ran on `git commit`, so you only need:\n   ```bash\n   mypy core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n   pytest tests/\n   ```\n   Without the hook, also run ruff by hand:\n   ```bash\n   ruff check core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n   ruff format --check core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n   mypy core-api/src/ core-storage-api/src/\n   pytest tests/\n   ```\n6. **Open a PR against `main`.** Fill out the PR template. Branch protection requires CI green, DCO check green, and ≥1 maintainer approval before merge.\n7. **Respond to review.** Expect at least one round of feedback.\n\n## Commit messages\n\nWe use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/). The\nsubject line must be `<type>(<optional-scope>): <subject>`, with the\ntype drawn from this list:\n\n| Type | Effect on the next release |\n|---|---|\n| `feat` | Minor bump |\n| `fix` | Patch bump |\n| `perf` | Patch bump |\n| `deps` | Patch bump (auto-applied by Dependabot) |\n| `revert` | Patch bump |\n| `docs` | No release impact, surfaces in CHANGELOG |\n| `refactor` | No release impact, surfaces in CHANGELOG |\n| `test`, `build`, `ci`, `chore` | Hidden from CHANGELOG, no release impact |\n\nAppend `!` (`feat!: …`) or a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer for changes\nthat break the [Public API](README.md#public-api--stability) — these\ntrigger a major bump once we ship 1.0.0. Before 1.0.0 they're treated\nas minor (`bump-minor-pre-major: true` in `release-please-config.json`).\n\n**Scopes** (optional but encouraged): `core-api`, `core-storage-api`,\n`core-worker`, `plugin`, `common`, `mcp`, `skill`, `e2e`, `benchmarks`,\n`docs`, `ci`.\n\n**Other rules:**\n\n- Subject line under 72 characters, imperative mood (\"add X\", not \"added X\").\n- Include context in the body when the change is non-obvious.\n- One logical change per commit.\n\n**Squash-merge note:** PR titles must themselves be Conventional Commits,\nbecause the squash-merge commit on `main` is what release-please reads.\nReviewers will rename PR titles before merging if needed.\n\n## Sign-off (DCO)\n\nEvery commit must carry a `Signed-off-by:` trailer asserting the\n[Developer Certificate of Origin](https://developercertificate.org/) —\na one-paragraph statement that you have the right to submit the work\nunder the project's license. This is a lightweight alternative to a CLA\nand is what the Linux kernel, Docker, and GitLab use.\n\nSign off automatically with `git commit -s`:\n\n```bash","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":140,"totalLines":183,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/CONTRIBUTING.md","time":{"start":1780729360450,"end":1780729360452}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055aada8abc9d1d5016a23c6105544819196f770a7f8414e2d"}},"id":"prt_e9bbdb03b001N4CNRoT2Ip2qzB","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbd8857001Jxpg3QelvxEs1Q"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780729360790,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbdb18a001zcyzuajhTpRblk","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"99d6abf239b22821c57c757843b918167bd6ab79","messageID":"msg_e9bbd8857001Jxpg3QelvxEs1Q","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":64869,"input":10170,"output":387,"reasoning":40,"cache":{"write":0,"read":54272}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780729362890,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbdb9c8001S1eqT9PGfSxR61","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","snapshot":"3f28bece8703c552d565e15928b7d013d8b876e2","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780729371732,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbdbf95001lrjLHbem09bv29","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","type":"text","text":"MemClaw itself exposes 12 MCP tools and explicitly uses some op-dispatched tools, not 37. That matters because a consolidation teaching aimed at shrinking MemClaw’s surface does not map cleanly to Spec Kit’s already budgeted 37-tool MCP surface.","time":{"start":1780729364373,"end":1780729371731},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_079a4abfdb54f220016a23c6145c548191a490fed6b7f5f5de","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729371791,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_lzJ8d5cuuF0uLOkxu2rT6i0i","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","offset":2320,"limit":230},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n2320:                     stored_target_agent_id=existing_data.get(\"agent_id\") if existing else None,\n2321:                     caller_agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n2322:                 )\n2323:                 if trust < min_level:\n2324:                     return _with_latency(\n2325:                         _error_response(\n2326:                             \"FORBIDDEN\",\n2327:                             f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n2328:                         ),\n2329:                         t0,\n2330:                     )\n2331:                 # TOCTOU narrowing: re-fetch the stored row immediately\n2332:                 # before the upsert and abort if the shape changed. A\n2333:                 # legitimate concurrent upsert could otherwise promote\n2334:                 # the stored scope between the gate read and the write\n2335:                 # below, letting a caller authorised for the looser\n2336:                 # earlier shape overwrite a stricter rule. Window is\n2337:                 # now reduced to (recheck → write), matching the delete\n2338:                 # path; storage-side conditional upsert remains the\n2339:                 # proper fix.\n2340:                 recheck = await sc.get_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=\"_keystones\", doc_id=doc_id)\n2341:                 recheck_data = (recheck or {}).get(\"data\") or {}\n2342:                 if (existing is None) != (recheck is None) or (\n2343:                     existing is not None\n2344:                     and recheck is not None\n2345:                     and (\n2346:                         recheck_data.get(\"scope\") != existing_data.get(\"scope\")\n2347:                         or recheck_data.get(\"agent_id\") != existing_data.get(\"agent_id\")\n2348:                     )\n2349:                 ):\n2350:                     return _with_latency(\n2351:                         _error_response(\n2352:                             \"CONFLICT\",\n2353:                             \"Keystone scope changed during operation; aborting upsert.\",\n2354:                         ),\n2355:                         t0,\n2356:                     )\n2357: \n2358:                 # Bump the tenant's write quota — matches every other MCP\n2359:                 # write handler (memclaw_write/doc/manage/evolve). OSS\n2360:                 # impl is a no-op; enterprise can wire real metering\n2361:                 # without touching this call site. Skipped for op=delete\n2362:                 # because deletes don't charge the write budget (mirrors\n2363:                 # the REST route skipping ``enforce_usage_limits`` on\n2364:                 # DELETE).\n2365:                 await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n2366:                 # Storage owns scope/weight/fleet/agent shape validation;\n2367:                 # surface its 422s directly so we don't drift from the\n2368:                 # canonical error list.\n2369:                 #\n2370:                 # Build the TypedDict explicitly so mypy catches missing\n2371:                 # required fields. Optional fields are only added when\n2372:                 # set (rather than included as None) because storage\n2373:                 # rejects e.g. ``\"fleet_id\": null`` for ``scope=tenant``\n2374:                 # (\"scope=tenant must not include fleet_id\") — mirrors\n2375:                 # the REST path's ``exclude_none=True`` behaviour.\n2376:                 payload: KeystoneUpsertPayload = {\n2377:                     \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n2378:                     \"doc_id\": doc_id,\n2379:                     \"title\": title,\n2380:                     \"content\": content,\n2381:                     \"scope\": scope,  # type: ignore[typeddict-item]\n2382:                     \"weight\": weight,  # type: ignore[typeddict-item]\n2383:                 }\n2384:                 if fleet_id is not None:\n2385:                     payload[\"fleet_id\"] = fleet_id\n2386:                 if agent_id is not None:\n2387:                     payload[\"agent_id\"] = agent_id\n2388:                 if author_user_id is not None:\n2389:                     payload[\"author_user_id\"] = author_user_id\n2390:                 doc = await sc.upsert_keystone(payload)\n2391:                 await log_action(\n2392:                     db,\n2393:                     tenant_id=tenant_id,\n2394:                     agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n2395:                     action=\"keystone.set\",\n2396:                     resource_type=\"keystone\",\n2397:                     resource_id=doc.get(\"id\") if isinstance(doc, dict) else None,\n2398:                     detail={\n2399:                         \"doc_id\": doc_id,\n2400:                         \"scope\": scope,\n2401:                         \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n2402:                         \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n2403:                         \"weight\": weight,\n2404:                         \"author_user_id\": author_user_id,\n2405:                         \"via\": \"mcp\",\n2406:                     },\n2407:                 )\n2408:                 await db.commit()\n2409:                 return _with_latency(\n2410:                     json.dumps({\"ok\": True, \"action\": \"set\", \"doc_id\": doc_id}, default=str),\n2411:                     t0,\n2412:                 )\n2413:             # op == \"delete\"\n2414:             # ONE trust round-trip for both the pre-lookup registration\n2415:             # check (≥ 1, anti-probing — collapses 404 vs. 403 leak so\n2416:             # unregistered callers can't probe ``doc_id`` existence)\n2417:             # and the post-lookup floor check. Ask ``_require_trust``\n2418:             # for the minimum the caller could possibly need (1), then\n2419:             # compare the returned trust level against the scope-derived\n2420:             # floor below.\n2421:             trust, not_found, terr = await _require_trust(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id, min_level=1)\n2422:             if not_found:\n2423:                 return _with_latency(\n2424:                     _error_response(\n2425:                         \"FORBIDDEN\",\n2426:                         f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' is not registered. \"\n2427:                         \"Register the agent by writing one memory first.\",\n2428:                     ),\n2429:                     t0,\n2430:                 )\n2431:             if terr:\n2432:                 return _with_latency(_error_response(\"FORBIDDEN\", parse_trust_error(terr)), t0)\n2433: \n2434:             # Look up the rule so the floor check sees the stored\n2435:             # ``scope`` + ``agent_id`` rather than trusting any caller\n2436:             # assertion. The documents-store GET ignores the system-\n2437:             # collection guard (it only fires on write/delete), so this\n2438:             # needs no new storage endpoint.\n2439:             existing = await sc.get_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=\"_keystones\", doc_id=doc_id)\n2440:             if not existing:\n2441:                 return _with_latency(\n2442:                     _error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", f\"Keystone '{doc_id}' not found.\"),\n2443:                     t0,\n2444:                 )\n2445:             existing_data = existing.get(\"data\") or {}\n2446:             min_level = keystone_min_trust(\n2447:                 existing_data.get(\"scope\", \"\"),\n2448:                 existing_data.get(\"agent_id\"),\n2449:                 caller_agent_id,\n2450:             )\n2451:             if trust < min_level:\n2452:                 return _with_latency(\n2453:                     _error_response(\n2454:                         \"FORBIDDEN\",\n2455:                         f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n2456:                     ),\n2457:                     t0,\n2458:                 )\n2459: \n2460:             # TOCTOU narrowing: re-fetch the stored row immediately\n2461:             # before the delete and abort if the shape changed. Without\n2462:             # this, a legitimate concurrent upsert can promote a\n2463:             # ``scope=agent`` rule to ``scope=fleet`` between the first\n2464:             # read and the storage delete, letting a trust-1 caller\n2465:             # delete a now-fleet rule it was never authorised for. The\n2466:             # remaining race window (recheck → delete) is a single\n2467:             # storage round-trip; the proper fix is a storage-side\n2468:             # compare-and-delete with preconditions. Mirrors the REST\n2469:             # delete path.\n2470:             recheck = await sc.get_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=\"_keystones\", doc_id=doc_id)\n2471:             if not recheck:\n2472:                 return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", f\"Keystone '{doc_id}' not found.\"), t0)\n2473:             recheck_data = recheck.get(\"data\") or {}\n2474:             if recheck_data.get(\"scope\") != existing_data.get(\"scope\") or recheck_data.get(\n2475:                 \"agent_id\"\n2476:             ) != existing_data.get(\"agent_id\"):\n2477:                 return _with_latency(\n2478:                     _error_response(\n2479:                         \"CONFLICT\",\n2480:                         \"Keystone scope changed during operation; aborting delete.\",\n2481:                     ),\n2482:                     t0,\n2483:                 )\n2484:             deleted = await sc.delete_keystone(tenant_id=tenant_id, doc_id=doc_id)\n2485:             if not deleted:\n2486:                 return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", f\"Keystone '{doc_id}' not found.\"), t0)\n2487:             await log_action(\n2488:                 db,\n2489:                 tenant_id=tenant_id,\n2490:                 agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n2491:                 action=\"keystone.delete\",\n2492:                 resource_type=\"keystone\",\n2493:                 resource_id=None,\n2494:                 detail={\"doc_id\": doc_id, \"via\": \"mcp\"},\n2495:             )\n2496:             await db.commit()\n2497:             return _with_latency(json.dumps({\"ok\": True, \"action\": \"delete\", \"doc_id\": doc_id}), t0)\n2498:         except httpx.HTTPStatusError as e:\n2499:             # storage_client._post / _delete call raise_for_status(); a\n2500:             # storage-side 422 (bad scope/weight) raises this — surface\n2501:             # the upstream status + detail instead of crashing the tool.\n2502:             # Mirrors routes/keystones.py:_surface_storage_error.\n2503:             try:\n2504:                 detail = e.response.json()\n2505:             except ValueError:\n2506:                 detail = e.response.text or str(e)\n2507:             return _with_latency(\n2508:                 _error_response(code_for_status(e.response.status_code), str(detail)),\n2509:                 t0,\n2510:             )\n2511:         except HTTPException as e:\n2512:             return _with_latency(_error_response(code_for_status(e.status_code), str(e.detail)), t0)\n2513:         except Exception as e:\n2514:             logger.exception(\"Unhandled error in memclaw_keystones_set\")\n2515:             return _with_latency(_error_response(\"INTERNAL_ERROR\", str(e)), t0)\n2516: \n2517: \n2518: # ── Mountable app + lifespan ──\n2519: \n2520: _mcp_starlette_app = mcp.streamable_http_app()\n2521: \n2522: \n2523: def get_mcp_app() -> ASGIApp:\n2524:     return MCPAuthMiddleware(_mcp_starlette_app)\n2525: \n2526: \n2527: @contextlib.asynccontextmanager\n2528: async def mcp_lifespan():\n2529:     \"\"\"Run MCP session manager lifecycle. Enter during FastAPI lifespan.\"\"\"\n2530:     async with mcp.session_manager.run():\n2531:         yield\n2532: \n2533: \n2534: # ── SoT registration ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n2535: # Triggers loading of every `core_api.tools.memclaw_*.py` spec module. Each\n2536: # spec module registers itself in the REGISTRY and calls `mcp_register(mcp, spec)`\n2537: # to wire the handler to FastMCP. This import must run AFTER the 16 handler\n2538: # functions above are defined — spec modules reference them via\n2539: # `core_api.mcp_server.memclaw_X` attribute lookup.\n2540: # The `noqa: E402,F401` silences \"module-level import not at top\" and\n2541: # \"imported but unused\" — both are intentional.\n2542: from core_api import tools  # noqa: F401\n\n(End of file - total 2542 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"                    stored_target_agent_id=existing_data.get(\"agent_id\") if existing else None,\n                    caller_agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n                )\n                if trust < min_level:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"FORBIDDEN\",\n                            f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                # TOCTOU narrowing: re-fetch the stored row immediately\n                # before the upsert and abort if the shape changed. A\n                # legitimate concurrent upsert could otherwise promote\n                # the stored scope between the gate read and the write\n                # below, letting a caller authorised for the looser\n                # earlier shape overwrite a stricter rule. Window is\n                # now reduced to (recheck → write), matching the delete\n                # path; storage-side conditional upsert remains the\n                # proper fix.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","text":"                    stored_target_agent_id=existing_data.get(\"agent_id\") if existing else None,\n                    caller_agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n                )\n                if trust < min_level:\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"FORBIDDEN\",\n                            f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n                # TOCTOU narrowing: re-fetch the stored row immediately\n                # before the upsert and abort if the shape changed. A\n                # legitimate concurrent upsert could otherwise promote\n                # the stored scope between the gate read and the write\n                # below, letting a caller authorised for the looser\n                # earlier shape overwrite a stricter rule. Window is\n                # now reduced to (recheck → write), matching the delete\n                # path; storage-side conditional upsert remains the\n                # proper fix.\n                recheck = await sc.get_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=\"_keystones\", doc_id=doc_id)\n                recheck_data = (recheck or {}).get(\"data\") or {}\n                if (existing is None) != (recheck is None) or (\n                    existing is not None\n                    and recheck is not None\n                    and (\n                        recheck_data.get(\"scope\") != existing_data.get(\"scope\")\n                        or recheck_data.get(\"agent_id\") != existing_data.get(\"agent_id\")\n                    )\n                ):\n                    return _with_latency(\n                        _error_response(\n                            \"CONFLICT\",\n                            \"Keystone scope changed during operation; aborting upsert.\",\n                        ),\n                        t0,\n                    )\n\n                # Bump the tenant's write quota — matches every other MCP\n                # write handler (memclaw_write/doc/manage/evolve). OSS\n                # impl is a no-op; enterprise can wire real metering\n                # without touching this call site. Skipped for op=delete\n                # because deletes don't charge the write budget (mirrors\n                # the REST route skipping ``enforce_usage_limits`` on\n                # DELETE).\n                await check_and_increment(db, tenant_id, \"write\")\n                # Storage owns scope/weight/fleet/agent shape validation;\n                # surface its 422s directly so we don't drift from the\n                # canonical error list.\n                #\n                # Build the TypedDict explicitly so mypy catches missing\n                # required fields. Optional fields are only added when\n                # set (rather than included as None) because storage\n                # rejects e.g. ``\"fleet_id\": null`` for ``scope=tenant``\n                # (\"scope=tenant must not include fleet_id\") — mirrors\n                # the REST path's ``exclude_none=True`` behaviour.\n                payload: KeystoneUpsertPayload = {\n                    \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n                    \"doc_id\": doc_id,\n                    \"title\": title,\n                    \"content\": content,\n                    \"scope\": scope,  # type: ignore[typeddict-item]\n                    \"weight\": weight,  # type: ignore[typeddict-item]\n                }\n                if fleet_id is not None:\n                    payload[\"fleet_id\"] = fleet_id\n                if agent_id is not None:\n                    payload[\"agent_id\"] = agent_id\n                if author_user_id is not None:\n                    payload[\"author_user_id\"] = author_user_id\n                doc = await sc.upsert_keystone(payload)\n                await log_action(\n                    db,\n                    tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                    agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n                    action=\"keystone.set\",\n                    resource_type=\"keystone\",\n                    resource_id=doc.get(\"id\") if isinstance(doc, dict) else None,\n                    detail={\n                        \"doc_id\": doc_id,\n                        \"scope\": scope,\n                        \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n                        \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n                        \"weight\": weight,\n                        \"author_user_id\": author_user_id,\n                        \"via\": \"mcp\",\n                    },\n                )\n                await db.commit()\n                return _with_latency(\n                    json.dumps({\"ok\": True, \"action\": \"set\", \"doc_id\": doc_id}, default=str),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            # op == \"delete\"\n            # ONE trust round-trip for both the pre-lookup registration\n            # check (≥ 1, anti-probing — collapses 404 vs. 403 leak so\n            # unregistered callers can't probe ``doc_id`` existence)\n            # and the post-lookup floor check. Ask ``_require_trust``\n            # for the minimum the caller could possibly need (1), then\n            # compare the returned trust level against the scope-derived\n            # floor below.\n            trust, not_found, terr = await _require_trust(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id, min_level=1)\n            if not_found:\n                return _with_latency(\n                    _error_response(\n                        \"FORBIDDEN\",\n                        f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' is not registered. \"\n                        \"Register the agent by writing one memory first.\",\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            if terr:\n                return _with_latency(_error_response(\"FORBIDDEN\", parse_trust_error(terr)), t0)\n\n            # Look up the rule so the floor check sees the stored\n            # ``scope`` + ``agent_id`` rather than trusting any caller\n            # assertion. The documents-store GET ignores the system-\n            # collection guard (it only fires on write/delete), so this\n            # needs no new storage endpoint.\n            existing = await sc.get_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=\"_keystones\", doc_id=doc_id)\n            if not existing:\n                return _with_latency(\n                    _error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", f\"Keystone '{doc_id}' not found.\"),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            existing_data = existing.get(\"data\") or {}\n            min_level = keystone_min_trust(\n                existing_data.get(\"scope\", \"\"),\n                existing_data.get(\"agent_id\"),\n                caller_agent_id,\n            )\n            if trust < min_level:\n                return _with_latency(\n                    _error_response(\n                        \"FORBIDDEN\",\n                        f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n\n            # TOCTOU narrowing: re-fetch the stored row immediately\n            # before the delete and abort if the shape changed. Without\n            # this, a legitimate concurrent upsert can promote a\n            # ``scope=agent`` rule to ``scope=fleet`` between the first\n            # read and the storage delete, letting a trust-1 caller\n            # delete a now-fleet rule it was never authorised for. The\n            # remaining race window (recheck → delete) is a single\n            # storage round-trip; the proper fix is a storage-side\n            # compare-and-delete with preconditions. Mirrors the REST\n            # delete path.\n            recheck = await sc.get_document(tenant_id=tenant_id, collection=\"_keystones\", doc_id=doc_id)\n            if not recheck:\n                return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", f\"Keystone '{doc_id}' not found.\"), t0)\n            recheck_data = recheck.get(\"data\") or {}\n            if recheck_data.get(\"scope\") != existing_data.get(\"scope\") or recheck_data.get(\n                \"agent_id\"\n            ) != existing_data.get(\"agent_id\"):\n                return _with_latency(\n                    _error_response(\n                        \"CONFLICT\",\n                        \"Keystone scope changed during operation; aborting delete.\",\n                    ),\n                    t0,\n                )\n            deleted = await sc.delete_keystone(tenant_id=tenant_id, doc_id=doc_id)\n            if not deleted:\n                return _with_latency(_error_response(\"NOT_FOUND\", f\"Keystone '{doc_id}' not found.\"), t0)\n            await log_action(\n                db,\n                tenant_id=tenant_id,\n                agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n                action=\"keystone.delete\",\n                resource_type=\"keystone\",\n                resource_id=None,\n                detail={\"doc_id\": doc_id, \"via\": \"mcp\"},\n            )\n            await db.commit()\n            return _with_latency(json.dumps({\"ok\": True, \"action\": \"delete\", \"doc_id\": doc_id}), t0)\n        except httpx.HTTPStatusError as e:\n            # storage_client._post / _delete call raise_for_status(); a\n            # storage-side 422 (bad scope/weight) raises this — surface\n            # the upstream status + detail instead of crashing the tool.\n            # Mirrors routes/keystones.py:_surface_storage_error.\n            try:\n                detail = e.response.json()\n            except ValueError:\n                detail = e.response.text or str(e)\n            return _with_latency(\n                _error_response(code_for_status(e.response.status_code), str(detail)),\n                t0,\n            )\n        except HTTPException as e:\n            return _with_latency(_error_response(code_for_status(e.status_code), str(e.detail)), t0)\n        except Exception as e:\n            logger.exception(\"Unhandled error in memclaw_keystones_set\")\n            return _with_latency(_error_response(\"INTERNAL_ERROR\", str(e)), t0)\n\n\n# ── Mountable app + lifespan ──\n\n_mcp_starlette_app = mcp.streamable_http_app()\n\n\ndef get_mcp_app() -> ASGIApp:\n    return MCPAuthMiddleware(_mcp_starlette_app)\n\n\n@contextlib.asynccontextmanager\nasync def mcp_lifespan():\n    \"\"\"Run MCP session manager lifecycle. Enter during FastAPI lifespan.\"\"\"\n    async with mcp.session_manager.run():\n        yield\n\n\n# ── SoT registration ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# Triggers loading of every `core_api.tools.memclaw_*.py` spec module. Each\n# spec module registers itself in the REGISTRY and calls `mcp_register(mcp, spec)`\n# to wire the handler to FastMCP. This import must run AFTER the 16 handler\n# functions above are defined — spec modules reference them via\n# `core_api.mcp_server.memclaw_X` attribute lookup.\n# The `noqa: E402,F401` silences \"module-level import not at top\" and\n# \"imported but unused\" — both are intentional.\nfrom core_api import tools  # noqa: F401","lineStart":2320,"lineEnd":2542,"totalLines":2542,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py","time":{"start":1780729371786,"end":1780729371790}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_079a4abfdb54f220016a23c61ba9788191818e07154680b59b"}},"id":"prt_e9bbddc56001vzW5ZG5nsnp8T3","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729371812,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_E8OHJAptKyA4c0axTojUTTfe","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: <p align=\"center\">\n2:   <img src=\"static/images/memCLAW_logo_dark.png\" alt=\"MemClaw\" width=\"420\" />\n3: </p>\n4: \n5: <h3 align=\"center\">Fleet memory for AI agents &mdash; governed, shared, self-improving.</h3>\n6: \n7: <p align=\"center\">\n8:   <a href=\"LICENSE\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache_2.0-blue.svg\" alt=\"License\" /></a>\n9:   <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/stargazers\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/stars/caura-ai/caura-memclaw?style=social\" alt=\"GitHub Stars\" /></a>\n10:   <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/actions\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/ci.yml?label=CI\" alt=\"CI\" /></a>\n11:   <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/releases\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/v/release/caura-ai/caura-memclaw\" alt=\"Release\" /></a>\n12:   <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Discord-join-5865F2?logo=discord&logoColor=white\" alt=\"Join us on Discord\" /></a>\n13: </p>\n14: \n15: <p align=\"center\">\n16:   <a href=\"#quick-start\">Quick Start</a> &middot;\n17:   <a href=\"#features\">Features</a> &middot;\n18:   <a href=\"#performance\">Performance</a> &middot;\n19:   <a href=\"#mcp-model-context-protocol\">MCP</a> &middot;\n20:   <a href=\"#api-reference\">API Reference</a> &middot;\n21:   <a href=\"static/docs/integration-guide.md\">Plugin Docs</a> &middot;\n22:   <a href=\"CONTRIBUTING.md\">Contributing</a> &middot;\n23:   <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\">Discord</a>\n24: </p>\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## MemClaw — Fleet memory for AI agents\n29: \n30: MemClaw is open-source memory for **multi-tenant, multi-agent** AI fleets. Your agents store what they learn, find what the fleet knows, and get smarter with every interaction — learning from each other instead of repeating mistakes.\n31: \n32: Agents write plain text. MemClaw turns it into searchable, governed, self-improving memory.\n33: \n34: **One loop, three pillars: write, recall, compound** — every interaction makes the next one smarter.\n35: \n36: **Built for fleets, not single agents.** Public agent-memory benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval) measure one agent, one user, one long conversation — the single-chatbot shape. The deployment shape we see in production is the opposite: dozens or thousands of agents working on behalf of a company, sharing what they learn under governance. MemClaw is architected around that shape from day one — scoped memory, cross-agent outcome propagation, fleet-wide trust tiers — and competes on the axes that compound with agent count: latency, token efficiency, and governance. See [Performance](#performance) for the numbers, or read the [benchmarks write-up](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks).\n37: \n38: <p align=\"center\">\n39:   <img src=\"static/images/memclaw-concept.svg\" alt=\"MemClaw — Fleet Memory that Compounds\" width=\"700\" />\n40: </p>\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## Quick Start\n45: \n46: Three paths — pick the one that matches your setup:\n47: \n48: | Path | When | Time to first memory |\n49: |---|---|---|\n50: | **Managed platform** | Quickest. We host the DB + scaling. | ~2 min |\n51: | **Self-hosted (Docker)** | Privacy / on-prem / air-gapped. | ~5 min |\n52: | **OpenClaw plugin** | You already run an OpenClaw fleet — install MemClaw as a plugin against any of the above. | ~3 min |\n53: \n54: ### Managed Platform\n55: \n56: Get up and running in minutes — no infrastructure, automatic updates, usage analytics, and enterprise-grade security included.\n57: \n58: 1. **[Sign up free on memclaw.net](https://memclaw.net)**\n59: 2. Grab your API key from the dashboard\n60: 3. Connect via MCP or REST:\n61: \n62: ```json\n63: {\n64:   \"mcpServers\": {\n65:     \"memclaw\": {\n66:       \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n67:       \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n68:     }\n69:   }\n70: }\n71: ```\n72: \n73: > **Production / team use:** the quickstart key above is a **tenant-scoped credential** — fine for personal use, but a fleet of agents should bind each one to its own **agent-scoped credential** for trust gating, fleet membership, and per-agent keystones. Provision agent-scoped credentials atomically via [`POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md), or through the dashboard at `/settings/organization/api-credentials`. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix on the wire — scope is bound at mint time on the credential itself. The MCP server accepts the credential on either `X-API-Key: mc_…` or `Authorization: Bearer mc_…`. *(Pre-existing `mca_…` and `mci_…` keys continue to authenticate via back-compat.)*\n74: >\n75: > Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n76: \n77: ### Self-Hosted (Open Source)\n78: \n79: The fastest path is Docker Compose — one command brings up Postgres + pgvector + Redis + the API.\n80: \n81: > **Prefer not to use Docker?** Skip to [Manual deployment (Python + Postgres)](#manual-deployment) below for the bare-Python path.\n82: >\n83: > **No cloud API key, no external calls?** v2.0+ supports a self-hosted local embedder (`BAAI/bge-m3` via HuggingFace TEI) — see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md). The setup below walks through the OpenAI default; the local-embedder doc walks through the alternative.\n84: \n85: #### Prerequisites\n86: \n87: - **Docker Engine 24+** (Linux) or **Docker Desktop** (macOS / Windows). Confirm with `docker --version`.\n88: - **Docker Compose v2** (built into modern Docker). Confirm with `docker compose version`.\n89: - **Git** for cloning.\n90: - ~2 GB free disk for images + Postgres data volume.\n91: \n92: #### 1. Clone and configure\n93: \n94: ```bash\n95: git clone https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw.git\n96: cd caura-memclaw\n97: cp .env.example .env\n98: ```\n99: \n100: Set your AI provider in `.env` — minimal setup with OpenAI:\n101: \n102: ```env\n103: EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai\n104: ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai\n105: USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION=true\n106: OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\n107: ```\n108: \n109: > Without any AI keys the stack still starts — dummy providers return non-semantic embeddings, useful for testing the API surface.\n110: \n111: > 💡 **Want zero cloud API calls?** v2.0+ ships a self-hosted embedder\n112: > profile (`BAAI/bge-m3` on a [HuggingFace TEI](https://github.com/huggingface/text-embeddings-inference)\n113: > sidecar). Bring up the stack with `docker compose --profile embed-local up -d`\n114: > and set the four `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*` envs from `.env.example` — see\n115: > [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for the full setup.\n116: > Combined with `IS_STANDALONE=true` (below) this is a fully self-contained\n117: > deployment with no external API calls.\n118: \n119: <details>\n120: <summary>Other providers (Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter, self-hosted)</summary>\n121: \n122: | Provider | `.env` settings | Required key |\n123: |---|---|---|\n124: | **OpenAI** (default) | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai` | `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n125: | **Google Gemini** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=gemini` | `GEMINI_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n126: | **Anthropic** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=anthropic` | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n127: | **OpenRouter** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openrouter` | `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n128: | **Self-hosted (TEI / bge-m3)** | `--profile embed-local` + `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL=http://tei:80/v1`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL=BAAI/bge-m3`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=false` | none — runs locally |\n129: \n130: Anthropic, Gemini, and OpenRouter don't offer embedding APIs here — pair them with OpenAI (or with TEI) for embeddings. You can mix providers freely. Gemini uses the [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/) key-auth Developer API (no GCP project/ADC required). The self-hosted TEI row keeps `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai` because TEI speaks the same OpenAI-compatible API; see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for hardware sizing, GPU setup, and model swapping.\n131: \n132: </details>\n133: \n134: #### 2. Start the stack\n135: \n136: ```bash\n137: docker compose up -d\n138: ```\n139: \n140: By default this **pulls the multi-arch images from `ghcr.io`** (`linux/amd64` + `linux/arm64`) on first run — takes ~30 seconds. Subsequent `up` commands re-use the cached image (no registry round-trip, works offline). To pin a specific version, set `MEMCLAW_VERSION=v1.2.3` in your `.env`. To build from local source instead (e.g. when iterating on a fork), run `docker compose up --build --no-pull`.\n141: \n142: To upgrade to a newer image at the same tag (e.g. `:latest` after we cut a new release), run `docker compose pull && docker compose up -d`. Without an explicit `pull`, the local cache wins — there's no silent version drift.\n143: \n144: > **Offline / air-gapped operation**: depending on whether the image is already cached locally:\n145: > - **Image cached, no network**: `docker compose up -d` works as-is — `pull_policy: missing` doesn't try to pull when the image is present. Use `docker compose up --no-pull` if you want to be explicit.\n146: > - **No local image, no network**: `docker compose up --build --no-pull` (build from source, don't try to pull).\n147: > - **Strict no-network guarantee** (e.g. an air-gapped pipeline that should never reach `ghcr.io`): drop a `docker-compose.override.yml` setting `pull_policy: never` for both services — Compose then fails fast if the image is absent rather than attempting a pull.\n148: \n149: | Service | URL |\n150: |---|---|\n151: | Core API (REST + MCP) | http://localhost:8000 |\n152: | Core Storage API | http://localhost:8002 |\n153: | PostgreSQL (pgvector) | localhost:5432 |\n154: | Redis | localhost:6379 |\n155: \n156: #### 3. Verify\n157: \n158: ```bash\n159: curl http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health\n160: # {\"status\":\"ok\",\"database\":\"connected\",...}\n161: ```\n162: \n163: #### 4. Write and search\n164: \n165: ```bash\n166: # Write a memory (standalone mode — no API key needed)\n167: curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/memories \\\n168:   -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n169:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n170:   -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"content\": \"Our auth service uses JWT with 15-minute expiry.\"}'\n171: \n172: # Search for it\n173: curl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/search \\\n174:   -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n175:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n176:   -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"query\": \"authentication token lifetime\"}'\n177: ```\n178: \n179: The write response includes LLM-inferred `type`, `title`, `summary`, `tags`, `status`, and `importance_score` — all from a single `content` field.\n180: \n181: <details>\n182: <summary>Auth modes</summary>\n183: \n184: OSS supports three auth paths. Pick one and add it to your `.env`, then `docker compose up -d` to restart.\n185: \n186: **Standalone** — single-tenant (`tenant_id=\"default\"`), simplest for local / self-install:\n187: ```env\n188: IS_STANDALONE=true\n189: ```\n190: No API key required for REST. MCP still expects a non-empty `X-API-Key` header — any value works.\n191: \n192: > Pair Standalone mode with `--profile embed-local` (see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md)) for a fully self-contained deployment: no admin keys, no external API calls, all embeddings computed locally. Useful for offline / air-gapped environments and personal-laptop installs.\n193: \n194: **Admin key** — multi-tenant with full access:\n195: ```env\n196: ADMIN_API_KEY=your-long-random-admin-key\n197: ```\n198: Pass `X-API-Key: your-long-random-admin-key` and include `tenant_id` in request bodies / query params.\n199: \n200: **Shared gate** — for network-exposed OSS deployments:\n201: ```env\n202: MEMCLAW_API_KEY=your-shared-key\n203: ```\n204: Clients send `X-API-Key: your-shared-key` plus `X-Tenant-ID: <tenant>`.\n205: \n206: > See [AGENT-INSTALL.md](AGENT-INSTALL.md) for the full agent self-install walkthrough.\n207: \n208: </details>\n209: \n210: <details>\n211: <summary>Running tests</summary>\n212: \n213: ```bash\n214: # Unit tests (no DB needed)\n215: pytest tests/ -m \"unit\"\n216: \n217: # All tests (requires PostgreSQL)\n218: docker compose up -d db\n219: pytest tests/ -m \"not benchmark\"\n220: \n\n(Showing lines 1-220 of 965. Use offset=221 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"<p align=\"center\">\n  <img src=\"static/images/memCLAW_logo_dark.png\" alt=\"MemClaw\" width=\"420\" />\n</p>\n\n<h3 align=\"center\">Fleet memory for AI agents &mdash; governed, shared, self-improving.</h3>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"LICENSE\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache_2.0-blue.svg\" alt=\"License\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/stargazers\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/stars/caura-ai/caura-memclaw?style=social\" alt=\"GitHub Stars\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/actions\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/ci.yml?label=CI\" alt=\"CI\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/releases\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/v/release/caura-ai/caura-memclaw\" alt=\"Release\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Discord-join-5865F2?logo=discord&logoColor=white\" alt=\"Join us on Discord\" /></a>\n</p>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"#quick-start\">Quick Start</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#features\">Features</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#performance\">Performance</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#mcp-model-context-protocol\">MCP</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#api-reference\">API Reference</a> &middot;","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","text":"<p align=\"center\">\n  <img src=\"static/images/memCLAW_logo_dark.png\" alt=\"MemClaw\" width=\"420\" />\n</p>\n\n<h3 align=\"center\">Fleet memory for AI agents &mdash; governed, shared, self-improving.</h3>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"LICENSE\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/License-Apache_2.0-blue.svg\" alt=\"License\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/stargazers\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/stars/caura-ai/caura-memclaw?style=social\" alt=\"GitHub Stars\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/actions\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/ci.yml?label=CI\" alt=\"CI\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/releases\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/github/v/release/caura-ai/caura-memclaw\" alt=\"Release\" /></a>\n  <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\"><img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Discord-join-5865F2?logo=discord&logoColor=white\" alt=\"Join us on Discord\" /></a>\n</p>\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <a href=\"#quick-start\">Quick Start</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#features\">Features</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#performance\">Performance</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#mcp-model-context-protocol\">MCP</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"#api-reference\">API Reference</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"static/docs/integration-guide.md\">Plugin Docs</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"CONTRIBUTING.md\">Contributing</a> &middot;\n  <a href=\"https://discord.com/invite/aNfpgfpj\">Discord</a>\n</p>\n\n---\n\n## MemClaw — Fleet memory for AI agents\n\nMemClaw is open-source memory for **multi-tenant, multi-agent** AI fleets. Your agents store what they learn, find what the fleet knows, and get smarter with every interaction — learning from each other instead of repeating mistakes.\n\nAgents write plain text. MemClaw turns it into searchable, governed, self-improving memory.\n\n**One loop, three pillars: write, recall, compound** — every interaction makes the next one smarter.\n\n**Built for fleets, not single agents.** Public agent-memory benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval) measure one agent, one user, one long conversation — the single-chatbot shape. The deployment shape we see in production is the opposite: dozens or thousands of agents working on behalf of a company, sharing what they learn under governance. MemClaw is architected around that shape from day one — scoped memory, cross-agent outcome propagation, fleet-wide trust tiers — and competes on the axes that compound with agent count: latency, token efficiency, and governance. See [Performance](#performance) for the numbers, or read the [benchmarks write-up](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks).\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n  <img src=\"static/images/memclaw-concept.svg\" alt=\"MemClaw — Fleet Memory that Compounds\" width=\"700\" />\n</p>\n\n---\n\n## Quick Start\n\nThree paths — pick the one that matches your setup:\n\n| Path | When | Time to first memory |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Managed platform** | Quickest. We host the DB + scaling. | ~2 min |\n| **Self-hosted (Docker)** | Privacy / on-prem / air-gapped. | ~5 min |\n| **OpenClaw plugin** | You already run an OpenClaw fleet — install MemClaw as a plugin against any of the above. | ~3 min |\n\n### Managed Platform\n\nGet up and running in minutes — no infrastructure, automatic updates, usage analytics, and enterprise-grade security included.\n\n1. **[Sign up free on memclaw.net](https://memclaw.net)**\n2. Grab your API key from the dashboard\n3. Connect via MCP or REST:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n> **Production / team use:** the quickstart key above is a **tenant-scoped credential** — fine for personal use, but a fleet of agents should bind each one to its own **agent-scoped credential** for trust gating, fleet membership, and per-agent keystones. Provision agent-scoped credentials atomically via [`POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md), or through the dashboard at `/settings/organization/api-credentials`. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix on the wire — scope is bound at mint time on the credential itself. The MCP server accepts the credential on either `X-API-Key: mc_…` or `Authorization: Bearer mc_…`. *(Pre-existing `mca_…` and `mci_…` keys continue to authenticate via back-compat.)*\n>\n> Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n\n### Self-Hosted (Open Source)\n\nThe fastest path is Docker Compose — one command brings up Postgres + pgvector + Redis + the API.\n\n> **Prefer not to use Docker?** Skip to [Manual deployment (Python + Postgres)](#manual-deployment) below for the bare-Python path.\n>\n> **No cloud API key, no external calls?** v2.0+ supports a self-hosted local embedder (`BAAI/bge-m3` via HuggingFace TEI) — see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md). The setup below walks through the OpenAI default; the local-embedder doc walks through the alternative.\n\n#### Prerequisites\n\n- **Docker Engine 24+** (Linux) or **Docker Desktop** (macOS / Windows). Confirm with `docker --version`.\n- **Docker Compose v2** (built into modern Docker). Confirm with `docker compose version`.\n- **Git** for cloning.\n- ~2 GB free disk for images + Postgres data volume.\n\n#### 1. Clone and configure\n\n```bash\ngit clone https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw.git\ncd caura-memclaw\ncp .env.example .env\n```\n\nSet your AI provider in `.env` — minimal setup with OpenAI:\n\n```env\nEMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai\nENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai\nUSE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION=true\nOPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...\n```\n\n> Without any AI keys the stack still starts — dummy providers return non-semantic embeddings, useful for testing the API surface.\n\n> 💡 **Want zero cloud API calls?** v2.0+ ships a self-hosted embedder\n> profile (`BAAI/bge-m3` on a [HuggingFace TEI](https://github.com/huggingface/text-embeddings-inference)\n> sidecar). Bring up the stack with `docker compose --profile embed-local up -d`\n> and set the four `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*` envs from `.env.example` — see\n> [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for the full setup.\n> Combined with `IS_STANDALONE=true` (below) this is a fully self-contained\n> deployment with no external API calls.\n\n<details>\n<summary>Other providers (Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter, self-hosted)</summary>\n\n| Provider | `.env` settings | Required key |\n|---|---|---|\n| **OpenAI** (default) | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openai` | `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **Google Gemini** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=gemini` | `GEMINI_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **Anthropic** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=anthropic` | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **OpenRouter** | `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai`<br>`ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER=openrouter` | `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` + `OPENAI_API_KEY` |\n| **Self-hosted (TEI / bge-m3)** | `--profile embed-local` + `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL=http://tei:80/v1`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL=BAAI/bge-m3`<br>+ `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=false` | none — runs locally |\n\nAnthropic, Gemini, and OpenRouter don't offer embedding APIs here — pair them with OpenAI (or with TEI) for embeddings. You can mix providers freely. Gemini uses the [Google AI Studio](https://aistudio.google.com/) key-auth Developer API (no GCP project/ADC required). The self-hosted TEI row keeps `EMBEDDING_PROVIDER=openai` because TEI speaks the same OpenAI-compatible API; see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md) for hardware sizing, GPU setup, and model swapping.\n\n</details>\n\n#### 2. Start the stack\n\n```bash\ndocker compose up -d\n```\n\nBy default this **pulls the multi-arch images from `ghcr.io`** (`linux/amd64` + `linux/arm64`) on first run — takes ~30 seconds. Subsequent `up` commands re-use the cached image (no registry round-trip, works offline). To pin a specific version, set `MEMCLAW_VERSION=v1.2.3` in your `.env`. To build from local source instead (e.g. when iterating on a fork), run `docker compose up --build --no-pull`.\n\nTo upgrade to a newer image at the same tag (e.g. `:latest` after we cut a new release), run `docker compose pull && docker compose up -d`. Without an explicit `pull`, the local cache wins — there's no silent version drift.\n\n> **Offline / air-gapped operation**: depending on whether the image is already cached locally:\n> - **Image cached, no network**: `docker compose up -d` works as-is — `pull_policy: missing` doesn't try to pull when the image is present. Use `docker compose up --no-pull` if you want to be explicit.\n> - **No local image, no network**: `docker compose up --build --no-pull` (build from source, don't try to pull).\n> - **Strict no-network guarantee** (e.g. an air-gapped pipeline that should never reach `ghcr.io`): drop a `docker-compose.override.yml` setting `pull_policy: never` for both services — Compose then fails fast if the image is absent rather than attempting a pull.\n\n| Service | URL |\n|---|---|\n| Core API (REST + MCP) | http://localhost:8000 |\n| Core Storage API | http://localhost:8002 |\n| PostgreSQL (pgvector) | localhost:5432 |\n| Redis | localhost:6379 |\n\n#### 3. Verify\n\n```bash\ncurl http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health\n# {\"status\":\"ok\",\"database\":\"connected\",...}\n```\n\n#### 4. Write and search\n\n```bash\n# Write a memory (standalone mode — no API key needed)\ncurl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/memories \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"content\": \"Our auth service uses JWT with 15-minute expiry.\"}'\n\n# Search for it\ncurl -X POST http://localhost:8000/api/v1/search \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: standalone\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"tenant_id\": \"default\", \"query\": \"authentication token lifetime\"}'\n```\n\nThe write response includes LLM-inferred `type`, `title`, `summary`, `tags`, `status`, and `importance_score` — all from a single `content` field.\n\n<details>\n<summary>Auth modes</summary>\n\nOSS supports three auth paths. Pick one and add it to your `.env`, then `docker compose up -d` to restart.\n\n**Standalone** — single-tenant (`tenant_id=\"default\"`), simplest for local / self-install:\n```env\nIS_STANDALONE=true\n```\nNo API key required for REST. MCP still expects a non-empty `X-API-Key` header — any value works.\n\n> Pair Standalone mode with `--profile embed-local` (see [`docs/local-embedder.md`](docs/local-embedder.md)) for a fully self-contained deployment: no admin keys, no external API calls, all embeddings computed locally. Useful for offline / air-gapped environments and personal-laptop installs.\n\n**Admin key** — multi-tenant with full access:\n```env\nADMIN_API_KEY=your-long-random-admin-key\n```\nPass `X-API-Key: your-long-random-admin-key` and include `tenant_id` in request bodies / query params.\n\n**Shared gate** — for network-exposed OSS deployments:\n```env\nMEMCLAW_API_KEY=your-shared-key\n```\nClients send `X-API-Key: your-shared-key` plus `X-Tenant-ID: <tenant>`.\n\n> See [AGENT-INSTALL.md](AGENT-INSTALL.md) for the full agent self-install walkthrough.\n\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>Running tests</summary>\n\n```bash\n# Unit tests (no DB needed)\npytest tests/ -m \"unit\"\n\n# All tests (requires PostgreSQL)\ndocker compose up -d db\npytest tests/ -m \"not benchmark\"\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":220,"totalLines":965,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","time":{"start":1780729371808,"end":1780729371811}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_079a4abfdb54f220016a23c61ba988819192b066e974919c11"}},"id":"prt_e9bbddc95001ATs7wbN2izkQkG","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729371819,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_a0rkH40U17svwERhEuVrirpH","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/local-embedder.md","offset":280,"limit":60},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/local-embedder.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n280: embedding is set to `NULL` so the column can be widened to 1024-dim.\n281: **Follow the canonical procedure in the README's\n282: [Upgrading from v1.x](../README.md#upgrading-from-v1x) section** — it\n283: sequences DB snapshot, opt-in env var, migration trigger, and re-embed in\n284: the order that won't lose data.\n285: \n286: The procedure expects you to run a stand-alone backfill CLI to re-embed\n287: existing rows (`python -m core_storage_api.scripts.backfill_embeddings`)\n288: after the migration completes. Both the OSS standalone CLI and the\n289: event-driven `core-worker` task work; the README documents both. For\n290: multi-tenant production cutovers prefer the event-driven path.\n291: \n292: ## Switching back to OpenAI hosted\n293: \n294: Just unset `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL` (and the three other `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*`\n295: envs from the TL;DR) in your `.env` and restart `core-api`:\n296: \n297: ```bash\n298: docker compose up -d --force-recreate core-api\n299: ```\n300: \n301: You stay on the 1024-dim schema. OpenAI's `text-embedding-3-small` supports\n302: `dimensions=1024` natively (Matryoshka — produced by truncating from the\n303: model's native 1536-dim and L2-renormalizing on OpenAI's side). Setting\n304: `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=true` (the default when `BASE_URL` is\n305: unset) tells the SDK to request 1024-dim output. So:\n306: \n307: - **Schema dim is global** — all embeddings in the DB are 1024-dim regardless\n308:   of which provider produced them.\n309: - **Provider switch is just an env-var change** — no migration, no re-embed\n310:   required (though you may want to re-embed for vector-space consistency\n311:   if you've been writing under a different vendor — re-run\n312:   `python -m core_storage_api.scripts.backfill_embeddings` after switching).\n313: \n314: To stop the unused TEI container too, drop the `--profile embed-local` flag\n315: on the next `up`:\n316: \n317: ```bash\n318: docker compose down\n319: docker compose up -d   # no profile = no TEI sidecar\n320: ```\n321: \n322: ## Troubleshooting\n323: \n324: * **`tei` healthcheck fails on first boot for several minutes.** First-time\n325:   model download can be slow (~2 GB for bge-m3). The healthcheck has 30\n326:   retries and `start_period: 60s` to cover this. Subsequent boots reuse the\n327:   `tei_cache` volume and come up in seconds.\n328: * **`core-api` logs `400 Bad Request` from `/v1/embeddings`.** Check that\n329:   `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=false` — TEI rejects the `dimensions=`\n330:   kwarg.\n331: * **Per-call latency jumps from ~130 ms to ~600 ms under concurrent load.**\n332:   Single-replica TEI queues requests in dynamic batching. Add a second\n333:   replica behind nginx/LB.\n334: * **`413 Payload Too Large` on long writes.** The compose `command:` includes\n335:   `--auto-truncate` so this should not happen with bge-m3 (8K context).\n336:   If it does, you've swapped to a 512-ctx model — pick something else or\n337:   pre-chunk in the application layer.\n338: * **`up -d` succeeds but TEI is silent on every embed call.** `core-api`\n339:   is hitting OpenAI, not TEI. The four `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*` envs aren't\n\n(Showing lines 280-339 of 362. Use offset=340 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"embedding is set to `NULL` so the column can be widened to 1024-dim.\n**Follow the canonical procedure in the README's\n[Upgrading from v1.x](../README.md#upgrading-from-v1x) section** — it\nsequences DB snapshot, opt-in env var, migration trigger, and re-embed in\nthe order that won't lose data.\n\nThe procedure expects you to run a stand-alone backfill CLI to re-embed\nexisting rows (`python -m core_storage_api.scripts.backfill_embeddings`)\nafter the migration completes. Both the OSS standalone CLI and the\nevent-driven `core-worker` task work; the README documents both. For\nmulti-tenant production cutovers prefer the event-driven path.\n\n## Switching back to OpenAI hosted\n\nJust unset `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL` (and the three other `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*`\nenvs from the TL;DR) in your `.env` and restart `core-api`:\n\n```bash\ndocker compose up -d --force-recreate core-api\n```","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/local-embedder.md","text":"embedding is set to `NULL` so the column can be widened to 1024-dim.\n**Follow the canonical procedure in the README's\n[Upgrading from v1.x](../README.md#upgrading-from-v1x) section** — it\nsequences DB snapshot, opt-in env var, migration trigger, and re-embed in\nthe order that won't lose data.\n\nThe procedure expects you to run a stand-alone backfill CLI to re-embed\nexisting rows (`python -m core_storage_api.scripts.backfill_embeddings`)\nafter the migration completes. Both the OSS standalone CLI and the\nevent-driven `core-worker` task work; the README documents both. For\nmulti-tenant production cutovers prefer the event-driven path.\n\n## Switching back to OpenAI hosted\n\nJust unset `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL` (and the three other `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*`\nenvs from the TL;DR) in your `.env` and restart `core-api`:\n\n```bash\ndocker compose up -d --force-recreate core-api\n```\n\nYou stay on the 1024-dim schema. OpenAI's `text-embedding-3-small` supports\n`dimensions=1024` natively (Matryoshka — produced by truncating from the\nmodel's native 1536-dim and L2-renormalizing on OpenAI's side). Setting\n`OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=true` (the default when `BASE_URL` is\nunset) tells the SDK to request 1024-dim output. So:\n\n- **Schema dim is global** — all embeddings in the DB are 1024-dim regardless\n  of which provider produced them.\n- **Provider switch is just an env-var change** — no migration, no re-embed\n  required (though you may want to re-embed for vector-space consistency\n  if you've been writing under a different vendor — re-run\n  `python -m core_storage_api.scripts.backfill_embeddings` after switching).\n\nTo stop the unused TEI container too, drop the `--profile embed-local` flag\non the next `up`:\n\n```bash\ndocker compose down\ndocker compose up -d   # no profile = no TEI sidecar\n```\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n* **`tei` healthcheck fails on first boot for several minutes.** First-time\n  model download can be slow (~2 GB for bge-m3). The healthcheck has 30\n  retries and `start_period: 60s` to cover this. Subsequent boots reuse the\n  `tei_cache` volume and come up in seconds.\n* **`core-api` logs `400 Bad Request` from `/v1/embeddings`.** Check that\n  `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS=false` — TEI rejects the `dimensions=`\n  kwarg.\n* **Per-call latency jumps from ~130 ms to ~600 ms under concurrent load.**\n  Single-replica TEI queues requests in dynamic batching. Add a second\n  replica behind nginx/LB.\n* **`413 Payload Too Large` on long writes.** The compose `command:` includes\n  `--auto-truncate` so this should not happen with bge-m3 (8K context).\n  If it does, you've swapped to a 512-ctx model — pick something else or\n  pre-chunk in the application layer.\n* **`up -d` succeeds but TEI is silent on every embed call.** `core-api`\n  is hitting OpenAI, not TEI. The four `OPENAI_EMBEDDING_*` envs aren't","lineStart":280,"lineEnd":339,"totalLines":362,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/local-embedder.md","time":{"start":1780729371816,"end":1780729371818}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_079a4abfdb54f220016a23c61ba9908191b18004d5b78fccfc"}},"id":"prt_e9bbddca100121POrOa6jMALgM","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729371832,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_k2mOSLrIhpNQy7Ct1V1rZJXI","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/RELEASING.md","offset":1,"limit":90},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/RELEASING.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Release Process\n2: \n3: MemClaw follows [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/) and uses\n4: [release-please](https://github.com/googleapis/release-please) to manage\n5: releases automatically from [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/).\n6: \n7: The repo ships **two independently-versioned packages**:\n8: \n9: | Package | Path     | Tag format       | Baseline |\n10: | ------- | -------- | ---------------- | -------- |\n11: | backend | `.`      | `backend-vX.Y.Z` | 2.5.0    |\n12: | plugin  | `plugin/`| `plugin-vX.Y.Z`  | 2.5.0    |\n13: \n14: Backend and plugin release on independent cadences. Plugin fixes no longer\n15: require a backend release; backend changes don't force a plugin version\n16: bump unless the plugin source itself changes.\n17: \n18: ## How it works\n19: \n20: 1. Push commits to `main` using Conventional Commit messages (`feat:`,\n21:    `fix:`, `perf:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`, `chore:` etc.).\n22: 2. release-please reads `release-please-config.json` +\n23:    `.release-please-manifest.json` and routes each commit to one or both\n24:    packages **by path**: commits touching files under `plugin/**` bump the\n25:    plugin package; everything else bumps the backend package.\n26: 3. release-please opens a single combined Release PR\n27:    (`separate-pull-requests: false`) containing per-component sections in\n28:    `CHANGELOG.md` and updated version files for whichever packages had\n29:    changes.\n30: 4. Merging the Release PR tags each updated package (e.g. `plugin-v2.5.1`)\n31:    and triggers the corresponding release workflows.\n32: \n33: ## Version files release-please rewrites\n34: \n35: **Backend (`.`):**\n36: - `core-api/pyproject.toml` (`$.project.version`)\n37: - `core-worker/pyproject.toml` (`$.project.version`)\n38: - `core-storage-api/pyproject.toml` (`$.project.version`)\n39: \n40: **Plugin (`plugin/`):**\n41: - `plugin/package.json` (`$.version`) — handled by `release-type: node`\n42: - `plugin/openclaw.plugin.json` (`$.version`)\n43: \n44: `plugin/src/version.ts` is generated by `scripts/gen-version.sh` from\n45: `plugin/package.json` at build time — it is NOT in `extra-files`.\n46: \n47: ## Commit scope conventions\n48: \n49: To make changelogs scannable, prefix the conventional-commit description\n50: with a scope when it helps:\n51: \n52: - `feat(plugin): add deploy command retry`\n53: - `fix(core-api): handle null tenant_id in heartbeat`\n54: - `fix(plugin,core-api): align deploy payload schema`\n55: \n56: The scope is cosmetic — package routing is purely path-based. A commit\n57: that touches both `plugin/` and `core-api/` will bump **both** packages\n58: with the same conventional-commit type. Split such commits when the\n59: change is logically separable; bundle when the cross-cut is intentional\n60: (e.g. a new API endpoint plus the plugin client that calls it).\n61: \n62: ## Compatibility\n63: \n64: There is no hard handshake. Backend logs a warning when a heartbeat\n65: reports a plugin version below `MIN_RECOMMENDED_PLUGIN_VERSION`\n66: (`core-api/src/core_api/version_compat.py`). Bump that constant when a\n67: backend change requires a newer plugin.\n68: \n69: The plugin's install endpoint (`/api/v1/install-plugin`) stamps the\n70: installed plugin with **plugin's** version (`plugin/package.json`), not\n71: backend's `VERSION`. Both are reported in heartbeat payloads\n72: (`plugin_version`, `openclaw_version`).\n73: \n74: ## Manual emergency release\n75: \n76: If release-please is unavailable, bump the affected package's version\n77: files manually, update `CHANGELOG.md`, and tag with the component-\n78: namespaced format (`backend-vX.Y.Z` or `plugin-vX.Y.Z`).\n\n(End of file - total 78 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Release Process\n\nMemClaw follows [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/) and uses\n[release-please](https://github.com/googleapis/release-please) to manage\nreleases automatically from [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/).\n\nThe repo ships **two independently-versioned packages**:\n\n| Package | Path     | Tag format       | Baseline |\n| ------- | -------- | ---------------- | -------- |\n| backend | `.`      | `backend-vX.Y.Z` | 2.5.0    |\n| plugin  | `plugin/`| `plugin-vX.Y.Z`  | 2.5.0    |\n\nBackend and plugin release on independent cadences. Plugin fixes no longer\nrequire a backend release; backend changes don't force a plugin version\nbump unless the plugin source itself changes.\n\n## How it works\n\n1. Push commits to `main` using Conventional Commit messages (`feat:`,","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/RELEASING.md","text":"# Release Process\n\nMemClaw follows [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/) and uses\n[release-please](https://github.com/googleapis/release-please) to manage\nreleases automatically from [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/).\n\nThe repo ships **two independently-versioned packages**:\n\n| Package | Path     | Tag format       | Baseline |\n| ------- | -------- | ---------------- | -------- |\n| backend | `.`      | `backend-vX.Y.Z` | 2.5.0    |\n| plugin  | `plugin/`| `plugin-vX.Y.Z`  | 2.5.0    |\n\nBackend and plugin release on independent cadences. Plugin fixes no longer\nrequire a backend release; backend changes don't force a plugin version\nbump unless the plugin source itself changes.\n\n## How it works\n\n1. Push commits to `main` using Conventional Commit messages (`feat:`,\n   `fix:`, `perf:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`, `chore:` etc.).\n2. release-please reads `release-please-config.json` +\n   `.release-please-manifest.json` and routes each commit to one or both\n   packages **by path**: commits touching files under `plugin/**` bump the\n   plugin package; everything else bumps the backend package.\n3. release-please opens a single combined Release PR\n   (`separate-pull-requests: false`) containing per-component sections in\n   `CHANGELOG.md` and updated version files for whichever packages had\n   changes.\n4. Merging the Release PR tags each updated package (e.g. `plugin-v2.5.1`)\n   and triggers the corresponding release workflows.\n\n## Version files release-please rewrites\n\n**Backend (`.`):**\n- `core-api/pyproject.toml` (`$.project.version`)\n- `core-worker/pyproject.toml` (`$.project.version`)\n- `core-storage-api/pyproject.toml` (`$.project.version`)\n\n**Plugin (`plugin/`):**\n- `plugin/package.json` (`$.version`) — handled by `release-type: node`\n- `plugin/openclaw.plugin.json` (`$.version`)\n\n`plugin/src/version.ts` is generated by `scripts/gen-version.sh` from\n`plugin/package.json` at build time — it is NOT in `extra-files`.\n\n## Commit scope conventions\n\nTo make changelogs scannable, prefix the conventional-commit description\nwith a scope when it helps:\n\n- `feat(plugin): add deploy command retry`\n- `fix(core-api): handle null tenant_id in heartbeat`\n- `fix(plugin,core-api): align deploy payload schema`\n\nThe scope is cosmetic — package routing is purely path-based. A commit\nthat touches both `plugin/` and `core-api/` will bump **both** packages\nwith the same conventional-commit type. Split such commits when the\nchange is logically separable; bundle when the cross-cut is intentional\n(e.g. a new API endpoint plus the plugin client that calls it).\n\n## Compatibility\n\nThere is no hard handshake. Backend logs a warning when a heartbeat\nreports a plugin version below `MIN_RECOMMENDED_PLUGIN_VERSION`\n(`core-api/src/core_api/version_compat.py`). Bump that constant when a\nbackend change requires a newer plugin.\n\nThe plugin's install endpoint (`/api/v1/install-plugin`) stamps the\ninstalled plugin with **plugin's** version (`plugin/package.json`), not\nbackend's `VERSION`. Both are reported in heartbeat payloads\n(`plugin_version`, `openclaw_version`).\n\n## Manual emergency release\n\nIf release-please is unavailable, bump the affected package's version\nfiles manually, update `CHANGELOG.md`, and tag with the component-\nnamespaced format (`backend-vX.Y.Z` or `plugin-vX.Y.Z`).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":78,"totalLines":78,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/RELEASING.md","time":{"start":1780729371828,"end":1780729371831}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_079a4abfdb54f220016a23c61ba99c8191953a6f30de270368"}},"id":"prt_e9bbddcad001i7oYo5MP5ctBFJ","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729371853,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vmSFCr0o8xGvPVYqP4IAhDJV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docker-compose.dev.yml","offset":1,"limit":160},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docker-compose.dev.yml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Full local development stack — hot-reload, mirrors staging architecture\n2: # Usage: docker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml up -d\n3: services:\n4: \n5:   # ── Infrastructure ──────────────────────────────────────────────\n6: \n7:   db:\n8:     image: pgvector/pgvector:pg16\n9:     environment:\n10:       POSTGRES_USER: memclaw\n11:       POSTGRES_PASSWORD: changeme\n12:       POSTGRES_DB: memclaw\n13:     ports:\n14:       - \"5432:5432\"\n15:     volumes:\n16:       - pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data\n17:     healthcheck:\n18:       test: [\"CMD-SHELL\", \"pg_isready -U memclaw\"]\n19:       interval: 5s\n20:       timeout: 3s\n21:       retries: 5\n22: \n23:   redis:\n24:     image: redis:7-alpine\n25:     command: redis-server --appendonly yes\n26:     ports:\n27:       - \"6379:6379\"\n28:     volumes:\n29:       - redis_data:/data\n30:     healthcheck:\n31:       test: [\"CMD\", \"redis-cli\", \"ping\"]\n32:       interval: 5s\n33:       timeout: 3s\n34:       retries: 5\n35: \n36:   # ── Core Storage API (hot-reload) ───────────────────────────────\n37: \n38:   core-storage-api:\n39:     build:\n40:       context: .\n41:       dockerfile: core-storage-api/Dockerfile\n42:     # Run as the host user so __pycache__ files written next to\n43:     # bind-mounted source land with host-matching ownership. Without\n44:     # this, on Linux hosts where id -u != 1000 (the appuser uid baked\n45:     # into the production Dockerfile) Python hits PermissionError on\n46:     # every reload. Defaults to 1000:1000, which matches the image's\n47:     # appuser and keeps current behaviour on hosts where it already\n48:     # works (macOS Docker Desktop, Linux at uid 1000). Override via\n49:     # ``UID=$(id -u) GID=$(id -g) docker compose up`` or .env entries.\n50:     user: \"${UID:-1000}:${GID:-1000}\"\n51:     command: >\n52:       uvicorn core_storage_api.app:app\n53:       --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8002 --reload\n54:       --reload-dir /app/core-storage-api/src\n55:       --reload-dir /app/common\n56:     ports:\n57:       - \"8002:8002\"\n58:     volumes:\n59:       - ./common:/app/common\n60:       - ./core-storage-api/src:/app/core-storage-api/src\n61:     environment:\n62:       PYTHONPATH: /app/core-storage-api/src:/app\n63:       DATABASE_URL: postgresql+asyncpg://memclaw:changeme@db:5432/memclaw\n64:       POSTGRES_HOST: db\n65:       POSTGRES_PORT: 5432\n66:       POSTGRES_USER: memclaw\n67:       POSTGRES_PASSWORD: changeme\n68:       POSTGRES_DB: memclaw\n69:       POSTGRES_REQUIRE_SSL: \"false\"\n70:       ENVIRONMENT: development\n71:     depends_on:\n72:       db:\n73:         condition: service_healthy\n74:     healthcheck:\n75:       test: [\"CMD\", \"python\", \"-c\", \"import urllib.request; urllib.request.urlopen('http://localhost:8002/healthz')\"]\n76:       interval: 10s\n77:       timeout: 5s\n78:       retries: 5\n79:       start_period: 10s\n80: \n81:   # ── Core API (hot-reload) ───────────────────────────────────────\n82: \n83:   core-api:\n84:     build:\n85:       context: .\n86:       dockerfile: core-api/Dockerfile\n87:     # See core-storage-api above for the rationale on user mapping.\n88:     user: \"${UID:-1000}:${GID:-1000}\"\n89:     command: >\n90:       uvicorn core_api.app:app\n91:       --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --reload\n92:       --reload-dir /app/core-api/src\n93:       --reload-dir /app/common\n94:     env_file:\n95:       - env.dev\n96:       - path: .env\n97:         required: false\n98:       - path: .env.local\n99:         required: false\n100:       - path: .env.test\n101:         required: false\n102:     ports:\n103:       - \"8000:8000\"\n104:     volumes:\n105:       - ./common:/app/common\n106:       - ./core-api/src:/app/core-api/src\n107:       - ./migrations:/app/migrations\n108:       - ./plugin:/app/plugin\n109:       - ./static:/app/static\n110:     environment:\n111:       PYTHONPATH: /app/core-api/src:/app\n112:       POSTGRES_HOST: db\n113:       CORE_STORAGE_API_URL: http://core-storage-api:8002\n114:       REDIS_URL: redis://redis:6379/0\n115:       # Pass through provider keys from host\n116:       OPENAI_API_KEY: \"${OPENAI_API_KEY:-}\"\n117:       ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: \"${ANTHROPIC_API_KEY:-}\"\n118:       OPENROUTER_API_KEY: \"${OPENROUTER_API_KEY:-}\"\n119:       # Embedder experiment (A.5) — local TEI sidecar overrides\n120:       OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL:-}\"\n121:       OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS:-true}\"\n122:       OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL:-}\"\n123:       # Option B (instruction-aware query encoding) and Matryoshka truncation.\n124:       # Default instruction applied to all /api/v1/search calls; ingest path\n125:       # unchanged. Truncate-to-dim lets us run native-1024/2560/4096-dim models\n126:       # against an unchanged 768-dim schema (Qwen3-Embedding family with MRL).\n127:       EMBEDDING_QUERY_INSTRUCTION: \"${EMBEDDING_QUERY_INSTRUCTION:-}\"\n128:       OPENAI_EMBEDDING_TRUNCATE_TO_DIM: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_TRUNCATE_TO_DIM:-}\"\n129:       EMBEDDING_PROVIDER: \"${EMBEDDING_PROVIDER:-fake}\"\n130:       ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER: \"${ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER:-fake}\"\n131:       USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION: \"${USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION:-false}\"\n132:     depends_on:\n133:       core-storage-api:\n134:         condition: service_healthy\n135:       redis:\n136:         condition: service_healthy\n137:       tei:\n138:         condition: service_healthy\n139:         required: false  # only enforced when --profile embed-local is active\n140:     healthcheck:\n141:       test: [\"CMD\", \"python\", \"-c\", \"import urllib.request; urllib.request.urlopen('http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health')\"]\n142:       interval: 15s\n143:       timeout: 5s\n144:       retries: 3\n145:       start_period: 15s\n146: \n147:   # ── Local Embedder (opt-in via ``--profile embed-local``) ───────\n148:   # See docker-compose.yml for the full block + comments. This dev\n149:   # variant is identical so that ``--profile embed-local`` works the\n150:   # same way against the hot-reload stack.\n151: \n152:   tei:\n153:     image: ghcr.io/huggingface/text-embeddings-inference:${TEI_IMAGE_TAG:-cpu-1.7}\n154:     profiles: [\"embed-local\"]\n155:     command:\n156:       - --model-id\n157:       - \"${TEI_MODEL_ID:-BAAI/bge-m3}\"\n158:       - --auto-truncate\n159:     environment:\n160:       HUGGINGFACE_HUB_CACHE: /data\n\n(Showing lines 1-160 of 174. Use offset=161 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Full local development stack — hot-reload, mirrors staging architecture\n# Usage: docker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml up -d\nservices:\n\n  # ── Infrastructure ──────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n  db:\n    image: pgvector/pgvector:pg16\n    environment:\n      POSTGRES_USER: memclaw\n      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: changeme\n      POSTGRES_DB: memclaw\n    ports:\n      - \"5432:5432\"\n    volumes:\n      - pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data\n    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD-SHELL\", \"pg_isready -U memclaw\"]\n      interval: 5s\n      timeout: 3s","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docker-compose.dev.yml","text":"# Full local development stack — hot-reload, mirrors staging architecture\n# Usage: docker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml up -d\nservices:\n\n  # ── Infrastructure ──────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n  db:\n    image: pgvector/pgvector:pg16\n    environment:\n      POSTGRES_USER: memclaw\n      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: changeme\n      POSTGRES_DB: memclaw\n    ports:\n      - \"5432:5432\"\n    volumes:\n      - pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data\n    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD-SHELL\", \"pg_isready -U memclaw\"]\n      interval: 5s\n      timeout: 3s\n      retries: 5\n\n  redis:\n    image: redis:7-alpine\n    command: redis-server --appendonly yes\n    ports:\n      - \"6379:6379\"\n    volumes:\n      - redis_data:/data\n    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD\", \"redis-cli\", \"ping\"]\n      interval: 5s\n      timeout: 3s\n      retries: 5\n\n  # ── Core Storage API (hot-reload) ───────────────────────────────\n\n  core-storage-api:\n    build:\n      context: .\n      dockerfile: core-storage-api/Dockerfile\n    # Run as the host user so __pycache__ files written next to\n    # bind-mounted source land with host-matching ownership. Without\n    # this, on Linux hosts where id -u != 1000 (the appuser uid baked\n    # into the production Dockerfile) Python hits PermissionError on\n    # every reload. Defaults to 1000:1000, which matches the image's\n    # appuser and keeps current behaviour on hosts where it already\n    # works (macOS Docker Desktop, Linux at uid 1000). Override via\n    # ``UID=$(id -u) GID=$(id -g) docker compose up`` or .env entries.\n    user: \"${UID:-1000}:${GID:-1000}\"\n    command: >\n      uvicorn core_storage_api.app:app\n      --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8002 --reload\n      --reload-dir /app/core-storage-api/src\n      --reload-dir /app/common\n    ports:\n      - \"8002:8002\"\n    volumes:\n      - ./common:/app/common\n      - ./core-storage-api/src:/app/core-storage-api/src\n    environment:\n      PYTHONPATH: /app/core-storage-api/src:/app\n      DATABASE_URL: postgresql+asyncpg://memclaw:changeme@db:5432/memclaw\n      POSTGRES_HOST: db\n      POSTGRES_PORT: 5432\n      POSTGRES_USER: memclaw\n      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: changeme\n      POSTGRES_DB: memclaw\n      POSTGRES_REQUIRE_SSL: \"false\"\n      ENVIRONMENT: development\n    depends_on:\n      db:\n        condition: service_healthy\n    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD\", \"python\", \"-c\", \"import urllib.request; urllib.request.urlopen('http://localhost:8002/healthz')\"]\n      interval: 10s\n      timeout: 5s\n      retries: 5\n      start_period: 10s\n\n  # ── Core API (hot-reload) ───────────────────────────────────────\n\n  core-api:\n    build:\n      context: .\n      dockerfile: core-api/Dockerfile\n    # See core-storage-api above for the rationale on user mapping.\n    user: \"${UID:-1000}:${GID:-1000}\"\n    command: >\n      uvicorn core_api.app:app\n      --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --reload\n      --reload-dir /app/core-api/src\n      --reload-dir /app/common\n    env_file:\n      - env.dev\n      - path: .env\n        required: false\n      - path: .env.local\n        required: false\n      - path: .env.test\n        required: false\n    ports:\n      - \"8000:8000\"\n    volumes:\n      - ./common:/app/common\n      - ./core-api/src:/app/core-api/src\n      - ./migrations:/app/migrations\n      - ./plugin:/app/plugin\n      - ./static:/app/static\n    environment:\n      PYTHONPATH: /app/core-api/src:/app\n      POSTGRES_HOST: db\n      CORE_STORAGE_API_URL: http://core-storage-api:8002\n      REDIS_URL: redis://redis:6379/0\n      # Pass through provider keys from host\n      OPENAI_API_KEY: \"${OPENAI_API_KEY:-}\"\n      ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: \"${ANTHROPIC_API_KEY:-}\"\n      OPENROUTER_API_KEY: \"${OPENROUTER_API_KEY:-}\"\n      # Embedder experiment (A.5) — local TEI sidecar overrides\n      OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_BASE_URL:-}\"\n      OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_SEND_DIMENSIONS:-true}\"\n      OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_MODEL:-}\"\n      # Option B (instruction-aware query encoding) and Matryoshka truncation.\n      # Default instruction applied to all /api/v1/search calls; ingest path\n      # unchanged. Truncate-to-dim lets us run native-1024/2560/4096-dim models\n      # against an unchanged 768-dim schema (Qwen3-Embedding family with MRL).\n      EMBEDDING_QUERY_INSTRUCTION: \"${EMBEDDING_QUERY_INSTRUCTION:-}\"\n      OPENAI_EMBEDDING_TRUNCATE_TO_DIM: \"${OPENAI_EMBEDDING_TRUNCATE_TO_DIM:-}\"\n      EMBEDDING_PROVIDER: \"${EMBEDDING_PROVIDER:-fake}\"\n      ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER: \"${ENTITY_EXTRACTION_PROVIDER:-fake}\"\n      USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION: \"${USE_LLM_FOR_MEMORY_CREATION:-false}\"\n    depends_on:\n      core-storage-api:\n        condition: service_healthy\n      redis:\n        condition: service_healthy\n      tei:\n        condition: service_healthy\n        required: false  # only enforced when --profile embed-local is active\n    healthcheck:\n      test: [\"CMD\", \"python\", \"-c\", \"import urllib.request; urllib.request.urlopen('http://localhost:8000/api/v1/health')\"]\n      interval: 15s\n      timeout: 5s\n      retries: 3\n      start_period: 15s\n\n  # ── Local Embedder (opt-in via ``--profile embed-local``) ───────\n  # See docker-compose.yml for the full block + comments. This dev\n  # variant is identical so that ``--profile embed-local`` works the\n  # same way against the hot-reload stack.\n\n  tei:\n    image: ghcr.io/huggingface/text-embeddings-inference:${TEI_IMAGE_TAG:-cpu-1.7}\n    profiles: [\"embed-local\"]\n    command:\n      - --model-id\n      - \"${TEI_MODEL_ID:-BAAI/bge-m3}\"\n      - --auto-truncate\n    environment:\n      HUGGINGFACE_HUB_CACHE: /data","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":160,"totalLines":174,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docker-compose.dev.yml","time":{"start":1780729371836,"end":1780729371839}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_079a4abfdb54f220016a23c61ba9a481918de6b86b86a801a6"}},"id":"prt_e9bbddcb7001bsa2nJog37JTm9","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780729372217,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbdde37001uYSn47qNnazAFd","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"8d3cbb397c9737fadcc9312c1ccfcb5c2549ca4c","messageID":"msg_e9bbdb330001oIKn8qp7ipTi4b","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":77943,"input":13484,"output":437,"reasoning":22,"cache":{"write":0,"read":64000}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780729375275,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbdea28001sVZv67vuuzlNrf","messageID":"msg_e9bbddf3e001fV7Ek2fFjuUb6P","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","snapshot":"77db0362c83a8ee54cd6ebc6582c45c1a498c8f3","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729385286,"sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_9PnKgn2F8pqhTAgYkJlPdVT2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Public API|stability|SemVer|semantic|Breaking|version|fleet|trust|PII|quarantine|propagation|divergence","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","include":"README.md"},"output":"Found 59 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md:\n  Line 30: MemClaw is open-source memory for **multi-tenant, multi-agent** AI fleets. Your agents store what they learn, find what the fleet knows, and get smarter with every interaction — learning from each other instead of repeating mistakes.\n\n  Line 36: **Built for fleets, not single agents.** Public agent-memory benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval) measure one agent, one user, one long conversation — the single-chatbot shape. The deployment shape we see in production is the opposite: dozens or thousands of agents working on behalf of a company, sharing what they learn under governance. MemClaw is architected around that shape from day one — scoped memory, cross-agent outcome propagation, fleet-wide trust tiers — and competes on the axes that compound with agent count: latency, token efficiency, and governance. See [Performance](#performance) for the numbers, or read the [benchmarks write-up](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks).\n\n  Line 52: | **OpenClaw plugin** | You already run an OpenClaw fleet — install MemClaw as a plugin against any of the above. | ~3 min |\n\n  Line 73: > **Production / team use:** the quickstart key above is a **tenant-scoped credential** — fine for personal use, but a fleet of agents should bind each one to its own **agent-scoped credential** for trust gating, fleet membership, and per-agent keystones. Provision agent-scoped credentials atomically via [`POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md), or through the dashboard at `/settings/organization/api-credentials`. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix on the wire — scope is bound at mint time on the credential itself. The MCP server accepts the credential on either `X-API-Key: mc_…` or `Authorization: Bearer mc_…`. *(Pre-existing `mca_…` and `mci_…` keys continue to authenticate via back-compat.)*\n\n  Line 87: - **Docker Engine 24+** (Linux) or **Docker Desktop** (macOS / Windows). Confirm with `docker --version`.\n\n  Line 88: - **Docker Compose v2** (built into modern Docker). Confirm with `docker compose version`.\n\n  Line 109: > Without any AI keys the stack still starts — dummy providers return non-semantic embeddings, useful for testing the API surface.\n\n  Line 140: By default this **pulls the multi-arch images from `ghcr.io`** (`linux/amd64` + `linux/arm64`) on first run — takes ~30 seconds. Subsequent `up` commands re-use the cached image (no registry round-trip, works offline). To pin a specific version, set `MEMCLAW_VERSION=v1.2.3` in your `.env`. To build from local source instead (e.g. when iterating on a fork), run `docker compose up --build --no-pull`.\n\n  Line 142: To upgrade to a newer image at the same tag (e.g. `:latest` after we cut a new release), run `docker compose pull && docker compose up -d`. Without an explicit `pull`, the local cache wins — there's no silent version drift.\n\n  Line 229: Already running an OpenClaw fleet? Install MemClaw as a plugin against either the managed platform or your self-hosted stack:\n\n  Line 236: export MEMCLAW_FLEET=my-fleet\n\n  Line 239:   \"$MEMCLAW_URL/api/v1/install-plugin?fleet_id=$MEMCLAW_FLEET&api_url=$MEMCLAW_URL\" | bash\n\n  Line 245: The plugin claims the OpenClaw `memory` slot (replacing `memory-core`) and exposes the same 12 MCP tools. Full setup, agent prompts, and trust levels: [static/docs/integration-guide.md](static/docs/integration-guide.md).\n\n  Line 253: - **Tenant isolation** — row-level database separation per tenant; PII auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries\n\n  Line 254: - **Visibility scopes** — every memory is stamped at write time: `scope_agent` (private), `scope_team` (fleet-wide, default), or `scope_org` (cross-fleet). Cross-fleet recall is permissioned, not open\n\n  Line 255: - **Agent trust tiers** — four levels control cross-fleet reads, writes, and deletes. Agents are either provisioned atomically via `POST /admin/agent-keys/provision` (recommended — mints key + row + trust + fleet in one call) or auto-registered on first write (legacy fallback)\n\n  Line 260: - **Single-pass LLM enrichment** — every write auto-classifies into one of 14 memory types, generates title/summary/tags, scores importance, flags PII, and extracts entities — from a single `content` field\n\n  Line 261: - **Hybrid search** — pgvector semantic similarity + full-text keyword matching + knowledge graph expansion (up to 2 hops), ranked by composite score of similarity, importance, freshness, and graph boost\n\n  Line 263: - **Contradiction detection** — RDF triple comparison + LLM semantic analysis detects conflicting memories and automatically supersedes them, with full contradiction chain tracking\n\n  Line 275: - **Document store** — structured JSONB collections alongside semantic memories for exact-field lookups (customer records, config, task lists)\n\n  Line 289: Accuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n\n  Line 291: > Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n\n  Line 327: > For team or production use, swap the tenant-scoped key for an **agent-scoped credential** — atomic provisioning via `POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision` (or the `/settings/organization/api-credentials` wizard) mints the credential + Agent row + initial trust + fleet membership in one round trip. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix; scope is set at mint time on the credential. See [`docs/integration-without-plugin.md`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md). Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n\n  Line 339: | `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword recall with graph-enhanced retrieval; optional LLM brief |\n\n  Line 342: | `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n\n  Line 349: | `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author or remove keystone rules (`op=set\\|delete`). Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for `scope=fleet`/`scope=tenant` or another agent |\n\n  Line 351: > **Skill sharing** is now done via `memclaw_doc` — agents share a `SKILL.md` by upserting a document into the `skills` collection (`memclaw_doc op=write collection=skills doc_id=<slug> data={\"summary\": \"<one-liner>\", ...}`). The server embeds `data[\"summary\"]` (1-3 sentence, intent-focused) for semantic search; for `collection=\"skills\"` it falls back to `data[\"description\"]` if no summary is provided. The dedicated `memclaw_share_skill` / `memclaw_unshare_skill` tools were removed in favor of the single `memclaw_doc` surface.\n\n  Line 357: (recall, write, supersede), trust levels, common patterns, and\n\n  Line 404: Re-run the installer any time to pull the latest version.\n\n  Line 424: Tags follow SemVer with floating aliases — `:v1`, `:v1.0`, `:v1.0.0`, plus `:latest` for the latest stable release. Pull them in your own compose file or Kubernetes manifests instead of building from source.\n\n  Line 470:   Re-embedding is required; until rows are re-embedded, semantic search returns\n\n  Line 579: All routes are versioned under `/api/v1/`. Interactive Swagger docs at `/api/docs`.\n\n  Line 596: | `/search` | POST | Hybrid semantic + keyword search with graph-enhanced retrieval |\n\n  Line 629: | `/insights/generate` | POST | LLM-powered analysis. Focus: `contradictions`, `failures`, `stale`, `divergence`, `patterns`, `discover` |\n\n  Line 635: | `/agents` | GET | List registered agents with trust levels |\n\n  Line 637: | `/agents/{id}/trust` | PATCH | Set trust level (0-3) |\n\n  Line 661: | `/fleet/heartbeat` | POST | Plugin heartbeat — upserts node status, returns pending commands |\n\n  Line 662: | `/fleet/nodes` | GET | List fleet nodes with status (online/stale/offline) |\n\n  Line 663: | `/fleet/commands` | POST | Queue a command for a node |\n\n  Line 664: | `/fleet/commands` | GET | List command history |\n\n  Line 671: | `/version` | GET | Current version |\n\n  Line 674: | `/admin/fleets` | GET | List fleets across all tenants (admin key) |\n\n  Line 681: **Auth:** `X-API-Key` header for all endpoints. Admin endpoints require the admin key. Public (no auth): `/api/v1/health`, `/api/v1/version`, `/api/v1/tool-descriptions`.\n\n  Line 683: **Gateway-injected headers** (trusted only behind the enterprise gateway):\n\n  Line 691: These headers are honored unconditionally — `core-api` must not be network-exposed without a gateway that strips them from untrusted callers.\n\n  Line 769: │       ├── routers/               # Memory, entity, document, fleet CRUD\n\n  Line 812: ## Public API & Stability\n\n  Line 814: MemClaw v1.x follows [SemVer 2.0.0](https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html). The surfaces below are stable; everything else is internal and may change in any release.\n\n  Line 824: | `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword search over memories, with optional LLM-summarised brief. |\n\n  Line 827: | `memclaw_list` | Non-semantic enumeration with filters, sort, cursor pagination. |\n\n  Line 831: | `memclaw_insights` | Karpathy-Loop reflection: contradictions, failures, stale, divergence, patterns, discover. |\n\n  Line 834: | `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules for the current scope (tenant + fleet + agent merged). Call once per session. |\n\n  Line 837: > Skill sharing uses the generic `memclaw_doc` surface — write/read/query/search/delete on `collection=\"skills\"`. The server validates the slug and embeds `data[\"summary\"]` for semantic discovery (with a back-compat fallback to `data[\"description\"]` for skills).\n\n  Line 849: | Fleet | `POST /fleet/heartbeat`, `GET /fleet/nodes`, `POST /fleet/commands`, `GET /fleet/commands` |\n\n  Line 850: | Agents | `GET /agents`, `GET /agents/{id}`, `PATCH /agents/{id}/trust`, `POST /admin/agent-keys/provision` (atomic key + row + trust + fleet), `GET /whoami` (identity probe) |\n\n  Line 855: | System | `GET /health`, `GET /version`, `GET /tool-descriptions`, `GET /audit-log` |\n\n  Line 868: | `MEMCLAW_FLEET_ID` | Default fleet id for writes/heartbeat. |\n\n  Line 893: ### Internal (not covered by SemVer)\n\n  Line 895: Anything not listed above is internal and may change in any release without a major version bump:\n","metadata":{"matches":59,"truncated":false},"title":"Public API|stability|SemVer|semantic|Breaking|version|fleet|trust|PII|quarantine|propagation|divergence","time":{"start":1780729385267,"end":1780729385284}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0ad10af0c1d379fb016a23c6293c708191a531010def894400"}},"id":"prt_e9bbe1124001wxLG5O0Laa5UEt","sessionID":"ses_164436585ffexoEvsPd4ItVAfq","messageID":"msg_e9bbddf3e001fV7Ek2fFjuUb6P"}}
